commit_message:
launch_instance: remove wrong ERROR label

Having to try more than once before the instance responds to a ping
should not be classified as an error.

A small refactoring simplifies the code somewhat.

Change-Id: Id06efa88e88c29687d03d84329c099e86c7bc538

[{'created': '2015-11-14 14:17:18.000000000', 'message': 'Fix RetryFilter error

This patch allows launch_instance to succeed in some cases where
launching an instance would repeatedly fail because the RetryFilter
returns 0 hosts.

The error occurs frequently after a cluster build with the kilo scripts.
The patch fixes the problem by restarting nova-compute.

Change-Id: I74b78e6ecc70f51d00da010c10f98ff46f702af8
'}]
commit_message:
Fix RetryFilter error

This patch allows launch_instance to succeed in some cases where
launching an instance would repeatedly fail because the RetryFilter
returns 0 hosts.

The error occurs frequently after a cluster build with the kilo scripts.
The patch fixes the problem by restarting nova-compute.

Change-Id: I74b78e6ecc70f51d00da010c10f98ff46f702af8

commit_message:
Use DEVICE_OWNER_COMPUTE constant everywhere

Now that we have the constant defined, we should reuse it from other
code to avoid potential typos.

Change-Id: Iebb270be46b116df3441370dc1a6784571311aa9

(9 comments)

Questions inline.

Also, I was really hoping that we could find a way to have implicit address scopes for everything. As I pointed out in the router code inline, we have logic trying to infer this and this is even a pain point for API callers.

For example, if I'm scripting app connectivity setups between instances, I can ask Nova or Neutron for the IP addresses of those instances. However, I have no way to know if I can setup the instances to use each other's private IP addresses to communicate without fetching their networks and crawling router interfaces to see if they are connected.

I want a standard way to ask Neutron if two L3 addresses can communicate directly regardless of the use of subnetpools. This has uses inside and outside that I think are well worth it if we can come up with a way to make sure every subnet has a scope."}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-06-10 17:54:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Specification for Trove monitoring framework

This specification is a draft for discussion of the Trove monitoring
framework. In normal course, this specification would only get sent
for review once we've had a lot more of the design and architecture
finalized. I am send this up early to get a sense of the community on
the approach; it would be pointless to do a lot more if the community
does not agree with the approach.

I believe it reflects the discussion(s) we had on the subject at
summit. At this stage this is a work-in-progress for review, please
treat this as an RFC.

Change-Id: I5186ec7577f21ecb2a4b13828a5d16b6202faec7

commit_message:
Add bash-completion/complete selection for command list parsing

gnocchi commands supports complete only (not supported bash-completion)
For supporting, it adds bash-completion/complete detection
in generate_command.
Instead, it removes specify "bash-completion" in generate_subcommand.

i.e call relation is follows
  generate_subcommand <= remove specify "bash-completion"
                         remove set subcommands
    generate_command  <= add method detection
                         newly set subcommands
    discover_and_generate_subcommands
       discover_subcommands  <= use subcommands
                                for bash-completion or complete

Change-Id: Ia076114aa7fda218ed6fc349951df536e11fb710
Closes-Bug: #1514705

commit_message:
add "unreleased" release notes page

We need a release notes page to show notes for unreleased versions by
scanning the "current" branch. This ensures that notes files cannot be
merged if they break the releasenotes job.

Change-Id: Ie1277428a3053d183df73bac882adc8aa0ac1079

commit_message:
Keep get_upstart_logs from hanging

If get_upstart_logs.sh is used after a partial or failed cluster build,
not all node VMs may be up. Therefore, the script must not wait
indefinitely for any node's ssh server to respond.

With this patch, ssh_env_for_node no longer waits for the ssh server.
Where that is needed (in test-once), it is now done in a separate call.

get_upstart_logs now checks (only) once whether each ssh server is up
before trying to fetch the logs.

Change-Id: I07314495a432dc2ce176233fac85a4c85406ef84

commit_message:
Adding --insecure flag

 * Added '--insecure' flag in order to disable
 SSL/TLS certificate verification (other projects have
 this flag as well)

 * By default the value is False
 * Small refactoring

Closes-Bug: #1515518

Change-Id: I1f3d2d5ad46810ba3f6189adb59b95d435d3ef6c

commit_message:
Enable pre_test_hook for functional test

This patch enables pre_test_hook to do the following preparation
for functional test:

 - Configure Senlin service to multi-engine mode
 - Set Senlin cloud_backend to openstack_test

Change-Id: I61a1d6f4e056236ad650df79b4413dbaf0293946

[{'account_id': 11360, 'date': '2015-10-27 10:10:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-10-27 10:10:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-27 10:10:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Awesome!  Thanks Lauren!!'}, {'account_id': 10348, 'date': '2015-10-27 12:14:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Thanks Lauren'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-11-02 02:24:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The numbers in here have slight differences with the charge on page 23 of https://www.openstack.org/assets/survey/Public-User-Survey-Report.pdf ... based on my understanding that are both Prod+Test numbers, so they should be the same?'}, {'account_id': 12651, 'date': '2015-11-03 20:59:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(14 comments)

Please see comments, Tom correctly identified discrepancies.  We also have additional projects that could be included.'}, {'account_id': 11360, 'date': '2015-11-05 19:00:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

It’s admittedly a bit confusing, but the data on page 22/23 of the user survey report includes both production stage deployments and test stage deployments (with the percentages for projects running production workloads and test/dev across both stages of deployments). In the past, we’ve used production stage deployments as the main filter, and then reported the percentages based on the projects running in those deployments. That’s how I calculated these data points, but there’s no graph in the report that’s a perfect match. Tom and I talked about whether we should update the graph in the report, because I’m not sure combining the production and test stage deployments is very useful. 

@Shamail, I agree we should pull in Rally (17%), Magnum (7%), Murano (7%), TripleO (4%), Congress (1%) and Kolla (2%). I can make those additions if everyone agrees.'}, {'account_id': 12651, 'date': '2015-11-05 19:50:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks Lauren.  That makes sense, I agree that production numbers would be better than prod+test as long as the source is published in the user survey.'}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-11-06 01:45:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Chatted with Lauren, and I think the numbers in this patch are good - it looks like the report might be the area needing the update.

Adding the extra projects makes sense to me.


@Lauren, if you need a refresher on amending a patch, steps are essentially:


* go to wherever you made this change
* Edit the files as appropriate
* git commit -a --amend
* git review

This will upload a new patchset to this review.


Often, I break my repository, so one other tip I use all the time: to get back to the state of the patch that is in the gerrit system, you can download it with

git review -d 239634

where 239634 is the number in the URL above.'}, {'account_id': 12651, 'date': '2015-11-06 01:56:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

commit_message:
Adds Liberty production deployment usage data

This JSON file tracks the percentage of production deployments
that reported using each project. The data is based off the
October 2015 user survey data and includes six new projects.

Change-Id: Ie4ccbfcd10b5938ef6bfce58600ece1a206112cb

commit_message:
Using extra-specs in cloned vols for Nimble driver

This patch uses the set extra-specs while cloning a volume. All
existing extra-specs: 'nimble:encryption', 'nimble:perfpol-name'
and 'nimble:multi-initiator' are being reflected in the cloned
volume.

In the existing code, the extra-specs were not being considered
while cloning volumes; the parent volume attributes were used
directly in the cloned volume. This patch uses the extra-spec
values if they are set or if not then uses the default values
for the same.

Change-Id: I7610377e557720038f77ebd318422456e658e2ce
Closes-Bug: #1507821
(cherry picked from commit 8484a234a8047019627184efbc2656f6ce2cb06d)

commit_message:
Update help message for cinder migrate

As per the doc bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/openstack-manuals/+bug/1363830
documentation for the cinder CLI should be updated to reflect that the host
needs to be given in the form host@backend#pool, and the docs for the
cli-reference are auto-generated from the client.

Change-Id: I66d41e05436782c3acd24f9633c4b67ca5c56b15

commit_message:
Check sio_storage_pools in check_for_setup_error

The ScaleIO driver fails to load if sio_storage_pools is not
specified in cinder.conf. This patch checks it in check_for_setup_error
and also check it in __init__.

Change-Id: I0fed70848ad2ecf3899b07058fabfa68df07edbd
Closes-Bug: #1497413
(cherry picked from commit ce575378da90ee3772438095b81a004ed7553102)

commit_message:
3PAR drivers volume size conversion is incorrect

The 3PAR drivers conversion of the volume size to gibibytes (GiBs) is
incorrect, resulting in slightly smaller volumes than expected. The
drivers were assuming the input was gigabytes (GBs) when in fact the
input was gibibytes (GiBs) as documented by the cinder API.

Change-Id: I5c86f506790723195f8f9433c9e5eedddd53a4ab
Closes-bug: 1513158
(cherry picked from commit 0ed514cb0ac0cc5842d695a80a29784ec098e82b)

commit_message:
better format remote IDs for identity providers

remote-ids are a list, and we should format these values as such,
rather than python representations of lists/arrays.

Closes-Bug: 1478995

Change-Id: Ia6ced0fab2435b8cb486822c676c0dee32613abe

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Update create_volume API to use versionedobjects

The following patch updates create_volume API to use
volume versionedobjects.  Changes were made to be
backwards compatible with older RPC clients.  It
only includes changes to the core cinder code.
Changes in the drivers are left to each driver
maintainer to update.

Note that this patch DOES NOT try to use
object dot notation everywhere, since it would
increase the size of the patch.  Instead, it
will be done in subsequent patches.

Co-Authored-By: Michal Dulko <michal.dulko@intel.com>
Change-Id: Ic1b0f09132f8fc500b29650abbd57f18ea8bd9dd
Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-objects

Change-Id: Ief9c63e8bddb2b40bdef4465b9099cff33d7c3bc

commit_message:
[install] Fix indent of code block

In the previous patch, the indent problem of the list item was fixed,
but I forgot to adjust the indent of the code blcok just below it.
It leads to an unnecessary quote marks in a generated HTML.

commit_message:
Cleanup dhcp namespace upon dhcp setup.

In some cases when more than 1 DHCP agents were assigned
to a network and then they became dead, their DHCP ports
become reserved. Later, when those agents revive or start
again, they acquire reserved ports, but it's not guaranteed
that they get exactly same ports. In such case DHCP agent
may create interface in the namespaces despite that another
interface already exist. In such case there will be two
hosts with dhcp namespaces each containing duplicate ports,
e.g. one port will be present on two hosts. This breaks
DHCP.

Closes-Bug: #1509959

commit_message:
make schedule_to_every_node use real scheduler hint

force_hosts is a scheduler construct, however it's not one you can
directly set via the API. Because we don't enforce schema on hints it
was silently ignored. The supported way to do this is through a
slightly baroque pass through in availability zones.

availability_zone: "$ZONE:$HOST"

This can only be done by admins by default, so we need to handle to
also replace self.server_client with self.admin_manager.server_client.

Change-Id: I3e61f039acf3278e0231183c4a774caa91681f7a

commit_message:
Use defaults in create_resources instead of resource defaults

Resource defaults are bad and leaky, we can avoid needing them in this
case by using the third argument to create_resources() which is a hash
of defaults to apply to resources.

https://docs.puppetlabs.com/references/latest/function.html#createresources

Change-Id: Iefe949b30d1a41e97e602f058d67a38dcb8d66ad

commit_message:
Four minor fixes that make debugging better

While running a script against all of the existing clouds, there were
a few issues that popped up. Most notably:

- get_openstack_vars would bomb out if your cloud didn't have security
  groups (rax)
- nova boot has a "this is why your boot failed" field that we did not
  pass on to the user
- TaskManager debug output showed the cloud but not the region, which is
  confusing when you have clouds with more than one region
- The novaclient error message for when you pass in the wrong datatype
  for nics is "str has no attribute get" which does not tell you that
  what you did was pass in a dict when you were supposed to have passed
  in a list of dicts. The problem is easy to trap for, and in more
  extreme cases to provide a better error message for.

Change-Id: Ie4f7c68d0ff95e020042189937ce452e596802cf

commit_message:
Add Guru Meditation Report feature

Oslo_reports enables OpenStack projects to dump Guru Meditation
Reports with useful debugging information to files or stderr.

Closes-Bug: #1514504
Change-Id: Id35fb7dc8c31f304cbf1d9cca0d21b9d5e97865a

commit_message:
Move to oslo.db

Replace the sqlalchemy engine and session management with an oslo.db
facade. This does the work transparently and fixes connection
mismanagement.

Change-Id: If29ef3a7b7419c37273c13ca56af8ccdd66d971a
Implements: blueprint move-to-oslo-db

commit_message:
REST Amp Agent: Handle interfaces file too

The amphora agent should be able to add interfaces by using the
/etc/network/interfaces file as well as the /etc/network/interfaces.d/*.cfg
files.

Closes-Bug: #1507889
Change-Id: I7840931fc426a0c74386512dfae3666d223049f8

Last sync from oslo-incubator

oslo-incubator will cease to host common code soon. This is
hopefully the very last sync from oslo-incubator.

commit_message:
drop root on memcached

This patch add the USER directive to the memcached container.
It also removes the -u from the command line to launch
memcached, since it will already be run as that use.

Change-Id: I87d782a424df99fe1b5694debafa3c0c4a9aba27
Partially-Implements: blueprint drop-root

commit_message:
sriov: add extensions option to configuration file

The agent supports l2 agent extension manager, so the option should be
there.

Closes-Bug: #1515274
Change-Id: I4376c7422dba058c11bfaf10046bd97b17592ce3
(cherry picked from commit ce814a1c29482e6e2601f0101ff3473a1afee35a)

commit_message:
Fix for create_object

The swiftclient upload() API call returns a generator. We were
trashing this generator by trying to Munch-ify it. This caused
create_object() to not be happy.

Change-Id: I8d391f361778328cea9920e923584988c8048946

commit_message:
Change install script to use git.o.o

These mirrors have a better uptime than github.com and are under the
direct control of OpenStack's infra team.

Change-Id: I3fdddc5c6c3be3fe1b5f7b071401e66607bca5e7

commit_message:
Add reno for release notes management

As per the release process changes for liberty and mitaka [1], the
reno tooling is being added to the repository for the purpose of
implementing on-going release note additions.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-November/078301.html

Change-Id: Ibbf4dc43b1fd5704a72cc7af82ddccfb1464926b

Hi, Dean Troyer and Steve Martinelli,
  Sorry for the late rely, and thanks a lot for your review.
  Yes, just like Steve said, this patch didn`t make a change to the usage of --block-device-mapping, but only fix a bug about the parse of its parameters.
  So, the all parameters still keep the original format which describled in the CLI doc.
--block-device-mapping dev_name=<id>:<type>:<size(GB)>:<delete_on_terminate>.
  Right now, I have no idea how to simplify it, as all parameters is useful if user wants to customize the volume device, I think. So, please let me know if you have any better ideas about this, thanks in advance.'}]

commit_message:
Improve formatting in launch_instance

This patch removes the newline between the periods that are output each
second while waiting for neutron to come up.

It also adds a line to visually separate VM instance launches.

Change-Id: I2fd9baf140aa1842e64400b1e6bb31e8b0ee8da0

[{'created': '2015-09-30 19:05:39.000000000', 'message': "CG driver function should not access db

Currently the following CG driver interfaces don't pass in volumes
or snapshots to the driver. As a result, drivers have to retrieve info
from db. In this patch, these interfaces are changed so that drivers
don't have to access db.

Removing the access to db from driver CG functions will be handled by
separate patches.

* create_consistencygroup
* delete_consistencygroup
* create_cgsnapshot
* delete_cgsnapshot

Change-Id: I63287fd43927fc09dad77292ecfe561917f7bda5
Closes-Bug: #1501466

commit_message:
CG driver function should not access db

Currently the following CG driver interfaces don't pass in volumes
or snapshots to the driver. As a result, drivers have to retrieve info
from db. In this patch, these interfaces are changed so that drivers
don't have to access db.

Removing the access to db from driver CG functions will be handled by
separate patches.

* create_consistencygroup
* delete_consistencygroup
* create_cgsnapshot
* delete_cgsnapshot

Change-Id: I63287fd43927fc09dad77292ecfe561917f7bda5
Closes-Bug: #1501466

commit_message:
Fix races: wait for keystone, mysql

With this patch, the client scripts wait for the mysql server to come
up before trying to create any tables.

In addition, heat waits for keystone like several other clients scripts
already do.

These races were encountered when testing the kilo release with a
KVM backend.

Change-Id: I9beb15f46050c3f9e5de92e2a0a9f6ec29d3a6b8

commit_message:
Adding support for shared option in Network

Horizon currently lacks the 'shared' option when a Network
is created / updated.This patch introduces the shared option in
Horizon Network Create and Update forms.

Change-Id: I7bf2d17f0ca10640252fae70ec6e6065b0ff6726
Closes-Bug: #1508828

commit_message:
Add possibility to use list of qpid hosts in cinder

 adding qpid_hosts parameter in oslo messaging section
 qpid_hosts parameter is a list of Qpid HA cluster host:port pairs.

commit_message:
Explicitly say that ovs_redhat parent is ovs

Fix coding error where puppet autopreloaded provider before instead
of the provider being specifically defined. This fixes puppet 4 error:
Could not find parent provider ovs_redhat of ovs_redhat_el6

Change-Id: I96931b67dbc18087abe7d673b202ef976bee4f83

commit_message:
Add Manila active/passive HA section to HA Guide

Manila API HA is virtually identical to that of Cinder, so the Manila
active/passive HA section is similar to the Cinder one.  The Manila
doc points to the new resource agent repo.

Change-Id: I872c18216770f6bc22c2370bae91f1f495dd0e8f

commit_message:
Support angular workflow extension as a feature plugin

This patch does three things:
1) It adds the extensible service which can be used to allow plugins
to customize various containers by adding and removing items such as
workflow steps, table actions, and form fields.

2) It adds support for a "feature" plugin that can be used to add
angular modules that can then be used to customize various panels.
The feature plugin is different from a typical plugin in that it does
not add a dashboard or panel, it only adds angular modules, JS files,
HTML templates, spec files, styles, etc.

3) It updates the workflow service to make each workflow extensible
and adds IDs to the launch instance workflow steps so that this
workflow instance is now extensible.

An example feature plugin is available here:
https://drive.google.com/open?id=0Bye7buoZvOxFOXJvMTNNUTdNNUk

Documentation will be provided by this commit:
  https://review.openstack.org/244407

Implements: blueprint angular-workflow-plugin
Change-Id: I8b426b1644c26b1af063d570da19a75ac8c97c27

commit_message:
Split common logic of CI hooks to separate file

Manila contains CI hooks located in "contrib/ci" dir.
Split common logic to separate file to be able to just "source" it and
then use env vars and bash functions in different CI jobs and projects.

Current change allows to do two things:
 - Reuse env var "MANILA_TEMPEST_COMMIT" in third-party CIs
 - Wait for drivers init in other projects like OpenStack Rally. Where,
   for the moment, one of jobs fails because of absense of "waiting".

Usage:
 $ source %manila%/contrib/ci/common.sh
 $ echo $MANILA_TEMPEST_COMMIT
 $ manila_wait_for_drivers_init "/etc/manila/manila.conf"

Change-Id: I94514405628ab8337d1f4153e431f064614e3596

[{'created': '2015-11-10 21:17:40.000000000', 'message': "Test for object version hash changes

Use the ObjectVersionChecker fixture from oslo.versionedobjects to check
when Cinder's registered objects have a change (new remotable method,
new field, etc) that require a version bump.

Removes deps=requirements.txt from tox.ini since it's not necessary and
prevents us from pip installing oslo.versionedobjects[fixtures].

Closes-Bug: #1514926

commit_message:
Test for object version hash changes

Use the ObjectVersionChecker fixture from oslo.versionedobjects to check
when Cinder's registered objects have a change (new remotable method,
new field, etc) that require a version bump.

Fixes some registration problems along the way:

1. CinderObject doesn't need to be registered.
2. TestObject should be registered where it's used, not globally.

Removes deps=requirements.txt from tox.ini since it's not necessary and
prevents us from pip installing oslo.versionedobjects[fixtures].

Closes-Bug: #1514926

Change-Id: Id57c56a75ea11411e9e54104165bd44b577c1485

In general, it's a good idea to go through the logs for the services that could be related to your change (or all of them if you aren't sure) and filter for warning/error/trace/etc, especially if you see a job fail multiple times. While we run lots of tests on every submission and people recheck a lot, it's still really expensive to do, and should follow some due-diligence, at least after the first one.

Also, recheck is really supposed to be for when you've identified that you're suffering from an unrelated failure that is already known. Elastic-recheck can help with that, although with the issues we've had over the last 48 hours it's probably very far behind.

commit_message:
Replace N block_device_mapping queries with 1

The ExtendedVolumes post-processing extension used to do N
block_device_mapping queries (one query per instance in a 'nova list').
Instead, do one block_device_mapping query with an IN clause of
instance UUIDs.

Change-Id: I32a1bd0e05a7a938e531d00bedfab23a0bb68538
Partial-Bug: #1416132
Closes-Bug: #1359808

commit_message:
Remove vcpu resource from extensible resource tracker

This patch makes vcpu resource tracking explicit in the
resource tracker and removes the corresponding VCPU
resource plugin from the extensible resource tracker.

This is a first step towards removing the extensible
resource tracker in a future release. A follow-on
patch will add deprecation notices for the
extensible resource tracker.

DocImpact: default value of compute_resources has
changed to an empty list.

blueprint resource-objects
Change-Id: If4318ce1c942292ef041a0b5c800304544207cb4

[{'created': '2015-11-05 11:51:44.000000000', 'message': "Add reno for release notes management

Since reno is the new tool for Relnotes [1], we need to add it
to Nova and provide some Sphinx docs for Liberty and Mitaka.

I'm open to discuss how to provide current master relnotes in HTML,
given I would like to not only check YAML files but really see the
resulted HTML files for the master branch.

At the moment, my proposition is to have a master.rst file which
checks the master branch (by default) but we can also write a
mitaka.rst file asking for version 13.0.0, it should work.

commit_message:
Add reno for release notes management

Since reno is the new tool for Relnotes [1], we need to add it
to Nova and provide some Sphinx docs for Liberty and Mitaka.

Change-Id: Ibd74e62b6f36076dbec17dd146632fd42aad6eb2

commit_message:
Add "unreleased" release notes page

We need a release notes page to show notes for unreleased versions by
scanning the "current" branch. This ensures that notes files cannot be
merged if they break the releasenotes job.

Change-Id: Id9e9d62b8b87068f940c0beee8ce37f32ab48266

commit_message:
Add test coverage for both types of not-found-ness in neutronclient for floating

This adds coverage for the exceptions.NotFound case when we're getting
floating IPs from neutronclient. It makes the NeutronClientException case
the "legacy" one that we can remove when we fix that bug.

Change-Id: I9c8b20e076527f98085265755a2d2503c703f235
Partial-Bug: 1513879

commit_message:
libvirt: fix failure when attaching volume to iso instance

Attaching volume to iso instance results in failure like
this 'libvirtError: Requested operation is not valid: target
hda already exists'. The root device of iso instance is hda,
nova-compute should not assign hda to cinder volume again.

Note: this patch only address the issue of duplicate device
name 'hda', disk bus 'ide' cannot be hotplugged, so we should
stop iso instance first when attaching volume.

Closes-Bug: #1379212
(cherry picked from commit 2f0f67d17cfedef2da4b1215f8d9072172a0d04f)

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/unit/compute/test_compute.py
	nova/tests/unit/test_block_device.py

Change-Id: If9f848dc3a3788862d25692250746387c6b35286

commit_message:
Rearranges to create new Compute API Guide

Uses openstackdocstheme to match other content

Has a dependent change in project-config also so that
file will build to developer.openstack.org/compute
at https://review.openstack.org/#/c/231000/

Change-Id: Ic060a1e79e4b2f8695cb788ff4df018e0cfd3286

I really think we should figure out where in the neutron / neutronclient path this is going wrong. The only reason this can be triggered is that Neutron is getting a raw error from somewhere else that's fumbling up and not being correctly mapped in Neutron / neutronclient space. 

Let's address the root cause, not the surface one."}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2015-11-11 13:50:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

sdague: While I agree that addressing the root cause is worth doing I feel like you are shooting the messenger here. This is a clear regression in Nova. The previous code worked... and now it doesn't. I think it would be totally reasonable to apply this fix, or perhaps even revert I9229d882712df1ad57afbda7477fa4d72f4fd83c to get Nova working again with all previously existing neutronclient versions and then move forwards in fixing root causes once we have more tests in place."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-11-11 13:53:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Yeah, I agree with Dan Prince here - we should be fixing the regression in Nova first, so the fixed Nova client is able to handle the exception correctly regardless of whether Neutron client is working or broken.  As & when we mandate a new min version of the neutron client then we can reconsider the Nova code.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-11-11 14:15:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@danpb if that's the strategy than this patch should have that as an inline comment for the code, a bug reference about the bug that's being fixed to address this for real, and that bug having more info than a stack trace.

There was a lot of context around this bug not presented in the bug report, or the review."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-11-11 14:49:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Right, so I don't even think this is the first time we've gone round on this particular thing. It's extremely confusing and if we pull this out again, it'll likely be added back in the next time we see an L3-related change that needs to "fix" this again.

I think this needs to:

 1. Leave the catching of NotFound so that this patch doesn't regress us past the original fix
 2. Add back in the NeutronClientException 404 clause, with a comment to a neutronclient bug where that gets fixed

Once the neutronclient bug is fixed, we can remove that silly poking of the exception to determine the root cause and require the new-enough neutronclient.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-11-11 14:53:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I'd be +2 on a patch that handled it the way dansmith suggests"}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2015-11-11 15:05:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I feel like we are making this more complicated that it needs to be.

What if we simply propose the revert to I9229d882712df1ad57afbda7477fa4d72f4fd83c as-is. That patch included a test for the correct Neutronclient exception (it was removed) and basically has the logic in place that dansmith suggests (checking for NotFound and NeutronclientException).

I think this is a case where a revert is the safest approach. A revert would fix the functional issue at hand, give us the cleanest git-logs (I always like to see a revert when something got functionally broken). And then we can file a neutronclient bug on the desired behavior and then follow up with a brand new patch that fixes this correctly.'}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:33:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:54:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2

Perfect, thanks'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:56:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

Thanks for respining this. Looking forward to the neutronclient fix as well.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:56:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Code-Review

As john pointed out on irc just now, we probably want a test for both cases'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:57:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

seems like we loose coverage here, but I like the code bits.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:57:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2

I will follow up with a fix to the tests'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:57:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Code-Review

commit_message:
Handle a NeutronClientException 404 Error for floating ips

I9229d882712df1ad57afbda7477fa4d72f4fd83c introduced _safe_get_floating_ips
which returns an empty list of floating ips in cases where neutron returns
a 404. It also switched a check for NeutronClientException with NotFound.
The NotFound Exception isn't used by neutron client so allow for both cases.

Closes-bug: #1513879
Change-Id: I1d37a0dadd4c9055ba545906535bb3e40e70a0f0

Change the repos from stackforge to OpenStack

The links which are referring to stackforge repo even after they
moved to openstack are corrected by replacing stackforge
with openstack

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-12 22:37:48.000000000', 'message': "Fix tox py27 error

The backup.test_backupagent.BackupAgentTest.test_backup_impl_MongoDump
unit test throws the following error when we run tox -r -e py27:
AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'rfind'

The error is caused by a 'None' CONFIG_FILE value being passed into the
os.path.dirname(CONFIG_FILE) call.

The CONFIG_FILE value is derived from the return value of the
trove.guestagent.common.operating_system.file_discovery() method, which
shouldn't be None.

This commit ensures the file_discovery() method would never return a
'None' value.

Change-Id: Id2f1f72e1a9e303c7b59ff0d25c556bc89de4669
Closes-Bug: 1515642
"}]
commit_message:
Fix tox py27 error

The backup.test_backupagent.BackupAgentTest.test_backup_impl_MongoDump
unit test throws the following error when we run tox -r -e py27:
AttributeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'rfind'

The error is caused by a 'None' CONFIG_FILE value being passed into the
os.path.dirname(CONFIG_FILE) call.

The CONFIG_FILE value is derived from the return value of the
trove.guestagent.common.operating_system.file_discovery() method, which
shouldn't be None.

This commit ensures the file_discovery() method would never return a
'None' value.

Change-Id: Id2f1f72e1a9e303c7b59ff0d25c556bc89de4669
Closes-Bug: 1515642

commit_message:
Add port valid range

According to [1]
oslo.config can use portType to support the ability to set valid range
on port option values.
[1]: http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.config/cfg.html

Change-Id: Ie24adcd165b2f711ad7f32df1fc248c2d6afe6bc

[{'created': '2015-10-06 11:29:23.000000000', 'message': 'Manila list shows a single export location instead of an array

"export_locations" is a plural field. As discussed,
"list" operation should not show "export locations" anymore.
Hence, removed displaying of it at all for list operation.

Change-Id: I4ae0cd3760088f1982301aa6f23a5c2d40be2455
Closes-Bug: #1438365
'}, {'created': '2015-10-29 13:02:48.000000000', 'message': 'Manila list shows one export location not multiple.

"Export Locations" is a plural field. As discussed,
"list" operation should not show "export locations" anymore.
Hence, removed displaying of it in default mode of list operation.
Still, it can be displayed, if specified explicitly, with --columns,
wherein a string of comma separated column names, prefixed with
+/- can be given.

Change-Id: I4ae0cd3760088f1982301aa6f23a5c2d40be2455
Closes-Bug: #1438365

commit_message:
Manila list shows one export location not multiple

"Export Locations" is a plural field. As discussed,
"list" operation should not show "export locations" anymore.
Hence, removed displaying of it in default mode of list operation.
Still, it can be displayed, if specified explicitly, with --columns,
wherein a string of comma separated column names can be given.

Change-Id: I4ae0cd3760088f1982301aa6f23a5c2d40be2455
Closes-Bug: #1438365

commit_message:
Neutron-legacy: Remove LINUXNET_VIF_DRIVER option

A value is never assigned, and it ends up in the nova.conf file as:

linuxnet_interface_driver =

So, let's delete it.

Change-Id: Ibc270ce6ee622eee871df1f8c11f21e8be8280ee

Replace default route for inet6

When taking the IPv6 addresses from an interface, also update any routing
table entries.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-09 12:26:30.000000000', 'message': 'More support Sphinx >=1.3b1 and <1.3.1

Although https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171309/
says Sphinx >=1.3, the actual implementation does not
support Sphinx >=1.3b1 and 1.3.1.
I have seen Sphinx release notes and source codes for
those versions, and found that up to 1.2.3 used
init_values(self) and Sphinx from 1.3b1 used
init_values(self, warn).

So to change the code from >=1.3.1 to >1.2.3, it can
more support Sphinx >=1.3b1 and <1.3.1.

Change-Id: Ia73be8111d3af7f72aaf640e4c7c519a5d0b08c5
Partial-Bug: #1379998
Related-Bug: #1496882
'}]
commit_message:
More support Sphinx >=1.3b1 and <1.3.1

Although https://review.openstack.org/#/c/171309/
says Sphinx >=1.3, the actual implementation does not
support Sphinx >=1.3b1 and 1.3.1.
I have seen Sphinx release notes and source codes for
those versions, and found that up to 1.2.3 used
init_values(self) and Sphinx from 1.3b1 used
init_values(self, warn).

So to change the code from >=1.3.1 to >1.2.3, it can
more support Sphinx >=1.3b1 and <1.3.1.

Change-Id: Ia73be8111d3af7f72aaf640e4c7c519a5d0b08c5
Partial-Bug: #1379998
Related-Bug: #1496882

Hi Wanghao
I have some dump questions here...
1. does driver need to report consistencygroup_support=True in both pool level and back end level?
2. what if pool level and back end level return different values?

Thanks
Peter'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-09-25 03:45:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Hi Winston,

Yes, we discussed about this and agreed that changing from scheduling at "pool" level to "backend" level could break drivers with existing CG implementation. 

On a second thought, I want to ask driver maintainers with CG to take a look of this patch as well to see if this works for them.  If CG still works for them with this patch, we can still consider moving forward with this?

Potential problem is with update CG. 
Assume there is 1 volume type, 2 pools A and B on the same backend backend1. 
Volume type 1 is associated with PoolA on 
backend1, volume type 1 is also associated with PoolB on backend1. 
PoolA supports CG, but PoolB does not support CG. 
Create a CG with type 1.  Create volume A in PoolA with type 1 and add to CG.
Create volume B in PoolB with type1.
Update CG and add volume B to it.  We are validating volume B is of volume type 1 that is in CG. 
Now we end up with a volume in a pool that doesn't support CG in the CG. So the problem is there is this same volume type that both supports CG for PoolA and doesn't support CG for PoolB.  I doesn't seem to me it is practical to set up volume type like this, but this is an issue that could happen.

Wanghao submitted a patch earlier to fix the update CG issue but that will keep the scheduling of CG at the pool level.  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/223108/

I'm thinking whether we should make the following extra spec a requirement in the volume type that supports CG?
{'capabilities:consistencygroup_support': '<is> True'}.

Right now that is not required.  If it is required, then we shouldn't have the update CG issue above.  Thoughts?'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-09-25 03:49:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Hi Peter,

If your driver supports multiple pools, you should report capability at pool level.  I think this is no different from other capabilities.  Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 12924, 'date': '2015-09-25 05:12:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

For the Pure CG's it shouldn't matter as our array doesn't mess with pools at all. That in mind I'm ok with this change, but I do agree with should make sure the folks who actually use pools are ok with it."}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-09-25 08:17:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

guys, to fix this issue, we need to ensure a question first: whether all storage backends support pools level cg, or just support backend level cg. I think both cases possibly happen.
So only require creation of cg on pool level is not reasonable. I think we should support them both.

If your backend supports cg on backend level, then your cg will be scheduled on backend level. If not, it's same as now.
Maybe a configuration option can be added in cinder.conf or driver can report this capability itself?"}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-09-25 08:29:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

@xing-yang, About require adding extra spec {'capabilities:consistencygroup_support': '<is> True'} in volume_type. Since we didn't have the validation about this spec in common volume creation process(it also shouldn't IMO), requiring uses to follow this rule sounds no sense. Users could create a volume with volume_type 1 on pool B first, and maybe after a long time, they create a cg with volume_type 1 on pool A, and then add the volume to CG."}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-09-25 13:19:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Just a comment on our storage. I need to fully review yet.

The Dell Storage Center driver does not report pools. I've been thinking of exposing a capability by reporting it as a pool though. If I were to do that, CG creation for us would only be possible within the pool, not across multiple pools.

Just a data point for the discussion. What we may or may not do in the future shouldn't really have a big impact on this decision."}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-09-25 13:54:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Thanks everyone for feedback.  From what I've heard so far, this change will not break the existing CG implementation.

If you want to have a CG to contain volumes in the same pool, you can use just one volume type at CG creation time and have that volume type associated with one pool.  That is how CG is used in some drivers today.

Regarding wanghao's concern on extra specs getting changed after volume is created, I think that is a valid concern but it is also a more general problem regarding volume type.  Assume the user creates volume type1 that does not support dedupe, and creates volumeA with type1.  Then he/she changes extra specs of type1 to support dedupe.  So does volumeA support dedupe or not?  This problem may need to be addressed by introducing versioning for volume types, but that is a whole different issue to solve."}, {'account_id': 10628, 'date': '2015-09-25 14:58:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

Just try on VNX driver, this change will NOT BREAK current CG functionality.'}, {'account_id': 16917, 'date': '2015-09-25 15:26:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

This did not break our drivers implementations of cgs either'}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-09-28 02:22:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Thanks everyone review this patch. From huawei driver, this patch will NOT break CG creation too.

@xing-yang, thanks your clarification, I agree with your about the volume_type issue. 

So for this patch, I suggest we merge this patch to support backend level scheduling. 

@xing-yang, could you have a talk with winston about our discussion here if you have time? Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2015-09-28 02:30:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

We still need feedback from NetApp.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-09-28 16:07:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
CG creation should be scheduled on backend level

Currently, cinder scheduler schedules the CG creation
on pool level, that means if there are multiple volume
types in one CG if each volume type is associated with a
different pool (those pools under same backend), you can't
create the CG successfully.

According to the design of CG's, it should be scheduled on
backend level to support the case mentioned above.

DocImpact
UpgradeImpact
Change-Id: I335dbdd1d2b1146543148ccce8d52162804369f4
Closes-Bug: #1496655

commit_message:
grep check of "cinder type-list" should look for an exact match

thus avoiding the bug where a substring match could lead to a false
positive.

Change-Id: I29173c42d8c499238906aa91c04e18047f7d0599

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-07 21:43:39.000000000', 'message': 'use network context for Neutron scenarios

This permits users to create a network with the network context, or
use the new exiting_network context, to provide networks to Neutron
scenarios instead of always creating a new network. This makes it
possible to run Rally against Neutron Provider Network deployments
with "dumb" routers. It will also eventually permit us to deduplicate
some code by moving network creation into the network context.

Neutron scenarios that are benchmarking network creation continue to
create networks.

This deprecates network creation inside the other scenarios. Warning
messages are produced where appropriate.

commit_message:
Use network context for Neutron scenarios

This permits users to create a network with the network context, or
use the new exiting_network context, to provide networks to Neutron
scenarios instead of always creating a new network. This makes it
possible to run Rally against Neutron Provider Network deployments
with "dumb" routers. It will also eventually permit us to deduplicate
some code by moving network creation into the network context.

Neutron scenarios that are benchmarking network creation continue to
create networks.

This deprecates network creation inside the other scenarios. Warning
messages are produced where appropriate.

Change-Id: I404eee0f14f40e348b2916854ed193c59364c31b

currently notifications are emitted for v2 calls, but the
initiator field is not filled in.

        keystone/resource/controllers.py

Co-authored-by: sam leong <chio-fai-sam.leong@hpe.com>

commit_message:
Replace get_all_neutron_bridges by get_deletable_bridges

Currently LinuxBridge L2-agent[1] defines get_all_neutron_bridges which
lists all bridges managed by the agent including user-defined ones BUT
this method is only used by neutron-linuxbridge-cleanup[2] in order to
remove empty non-user-defined bridges returned get_all_neutron_bridges.

This change replaces this method by get_deletable_bridges which returns
bridges managed by LB agent which are "deletable" (ie: non user-defined).
This allows to simplify code and move the computation of "deletable"
bridges to LB agent code.

[1] neutron.plugins.ml2.drivers.linuxbridge.agent.linuxbridge_neutron_agent
[2] neutron.cmd.linuxbridge_cleanup

Partial-Bug: #1514548
Change-Id: I2f8a9a6982ce0ce77187ae4b7a58b3ef752aab34

commit_message:
Add ability to run Nova metadata under Apache2

This patch allows to run Nova metadata service using Apache
on port 80 under /metadata URL.

Change-Id: I18f3399738c31166eac884a9b0d5c4045d3f445c

commit_message:
always use constraints

Running test jobs without constraints is mostly a recipe for tears, as
it will allow for conflicting requirements which are no fun to
debug. Remove any conditionality here.

Change-Id: I51c916fa0a27b21b3342297f2a0e8563d1d5364c

Catching general falcon HTTP error instead of specific errors

commit_message:
Fixed errors in the resouce try/catch decorator

Catching general falcon HTTP error instead of specific errors

General exception handler had an error that caused an exception.  This was
caught by gunicorn which generated an HTML response instead of the response
we expect.

Fixed typo in MeultipleMetricsException.

Change-Id: I5fdf58a9c732df3cb980d4c498730ea639b0a5a3

commit_message:
Get rid of unused dependencies in requirements.txt

- anyjson is a dependency for oslo.serialization
- jsonrpclib (not used)
- iso8601 (not used)
- netaddr (not used)
- networkx (not used)

Change-Id: I49afc80a677fe71295b9d1f723a0c26c12d6993b

The cells job is failing on a race where an image is created
from an instance with a single volume attached, but we have
multiple (duplicate) BDMs for the instance so we end up with
multiple volume snapshots for the image, which later fails a
boot request using the snapshot image because the image has
duplicate BDMs with the same boot_index, which is invalid in

cinder to create a volume snapshot so we have the request
context and instance uuid in the logs for tracing.

Related-Bug: #1489581

commit_message:
Add logging to snapshot_volume_backed method

The cells job is failing on a race where an image is created
from an instance with a single volume attached, but we have
multiple (duplicate) BDMs for the instance so we end up with
multiple volume snapshots for the image, which later fails a
boot request using the snapshot image because the image has
duplicate BDMs with the same boot_index, which is invalid in
the request.

This just adds some debug logging when we actually call off to
cinder to create a volume snapshot so we have the request
context and instance uuid in the logs for tracing.

Change-Id: Iba8ad7cf40ba076e90abc8604187700166795c5d
Related-Bug: #1489581

commit_message:
pyasn1 and pyasn1-modules modules no more needed

The following change use Python 3.4 "cryptography" libraries instead of "pyasn1".
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/184868/

Clean up have been performed in requirements.txt

Closes-Bug: #1515917
Change-Id: I36877d27ac222908db7af6183628589dbcdf2968

commit_message:
change `swift post` to openstackclient cli command

with the release of osc 1.8.0, modifying object store account
properties is now available. use this mechanism and avoid setting
environment variable that are only helpful for swift CLI.

Change-Id: Ie51e3e2bb86162763f23d0a6bed36208811f89fc

commit_message:
Remove parameter defaults

Remove parameters that have sane defaults in the Heat templates.
In order to change these, one should use an environment file rather
than passing args to the deploy command. These commands should now
be considered deprecated in favor of the environment file.

Change-Id: Idbf85d455f348ed2ab9b34fe1dc95faec427a13f
Depends-On: Ifd740c50ee0e48e0cf50d9ebd9cc282155cb3a6d

commit_message:
Revert "Drop root for Horizon service"

This reverts commit f9ccb1c8829cef551b875c7c387530e7980414a7.

There are many issues with this patch that prevents it from working
under numerous circumstances. The implementation is entirely busted
on Ubuntu. Additionally, best practice for apache is to run as root.
Apache itself does the privlege dropping.

Change-Id: I4395debb7d32223fb3752a6d3e7c4d7672d29916

commit_message:
Make server.key/client.key as private in k8s node

At this time, server.key and client.key which are used by
kubernetes related daemon are readable. These keys should
be private.

Change-Id: I52232001f6983845f8d7de75486fe5672a57949a
Closes-Bug: #1515844

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-20 19:14:04.000000000', 'message': "Add Magnum config for default network driver per COE

Problem description:
Magnum should provide support for configuration of default
network drivers per COE. An example use case could be
a cloud operator who would like to have control of what
default container network driver should be used on a
per-COE basis. The cloud operator in this case should
be able to set the default network driver per COE in
/etc/magnum/magnum.conf.

Proposed fix:
Add 3 configuration list options to the
config in /etc/magnum/magnum.conf:
- kubernetes_default_network_driver
  (default='flannel')
- swarm_default_network_driver
  (default='docker')
- mesos_default_network_driver
  (default='docker')
When a baymodel is created and the --network-driver
attribute is not supplied, then the configured
default network driver for the selected COE will first
be checked against the list of allowed network drivers
for that COE, and if allowed, the configured default
network driver will be used for the new baymodel.

commit_message:
Add Magnum config for default network driver per COE

Problem description:
Magnum should provide support for configuration of default network drivers per
COE. An example use case could be a cloud operator who would like to have
control of what default container network driver should be used on a per-COE
basis. The cloud operator in this case should be able to set the default
network driver per COE in /etc/magnum/magnum.conf.

Proposed fix:
Add 3 configuration list options to the config in /etc/magnum/magnum.conf:
- kubernetes_default_network_driver
  (default='flannel')
- swarm_default_network_driver
  (default='docker')
- mesos_default_network_driver
  (default='docker')
When a baymodel is created and the --network-driver attribute is not supplied,
then the configured default network driver for the selected COE will first be
checked against the list of allowed network drivers for that COE, and if
allowed, the configured default network driver will be used for the new
baymodel.

Change-Id: I1e1d68c3348f609975b914926994bd79c1ef6d28
Closes-Bug: #1504664

commit_message:
Improve "server list" command to have the same output as "nova list".

"nova list" will also output "Task State" and "Power State" by default.
This patch improves "server list" command to have the same columns, but
not by default. These two columns will be output if --long is added.

The power state is an int, so also adds a formatter helper function
to translate it to human readable string, just as "Networks" does.

Change-Id: I0530a910bec03835839a5ba7687c66d5643338f3

commit_message:
Use oslo_config new type PortOpt for port options

The oslo_config library provides new type PortOpt to validate the
range of port now.
ref: https://github.com/openstack/oslo.config/blob/2.6.0/oslo_config/cfg.py#L1114

DocImpact
Change-Id: I9a3e4d13feef67b4a43936c6099b822e4f1f6a57
Closes-Bug: #1514702

commit_message:
Add Liberty release notes as reno yaml files

This commit takes all the Liberty release notes from the wiki here [1] and
moves them into reno yaml files.

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/ReleaseNotes/Liberty#OpenStack_Networking_.28Neutron.29

Depends-On: I0c9b6d9a0e77b57e3637260b6e73edfe78afe5ae

Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

commit_message:
Refactor test_server functional tests

* Launching services with 0 workers makes no sense and would soon
  be prohibited in oslo.service. Passing workers=1 means that a
  service will be run in a current process.
* Extract the dummy _check_active method to the base class.

Change-Id: Ib687bf1b321845098e0564ada46e68a7850b01c6

commit_message:
test_fields: Remove 'test_stringify' tests

This function is already validated by testing the superclass
'Enum' field. Unless the subclass changes this behavior, there is
no need to validate it a second time. Remove the tests.

Change-Id: I4a445393d9134cefe08c7e331172d7369c7fb0f2

(1 comment)

Hey Cedric - everything looks good except for how we're doing the string formatting - throughout this patch we're doing the following:

"Target info: pool: {}, type: {}, tier: {}.".format(tar_pool, tar_type, tar_tier)

but I think the preferred way to do the formatting in OpenStack is:

"Target info: pool: %(pool)s, type: %(type)s, tier: %(tier)" % ('pool': tar_pool, 'type': tar_type, 'tier': tar_tier)

or just "%s" for single value substitution.

Sorry I didn't notice this last time.'}, {'account_id': 13206, 'date': '2015-09-24 06:21:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-04 16:36:01.000000000', 'message': "Add retype logic in manage_existing for VNX

The manage existing api for VNX driver didn't check the volume type.
Add type check and retype the volume if its not match.
Raise ManageExistingVolumeTypeMismatch if volume type cannot be satisfied.

Details of the change:

  * In order to compare the type of the LUN and the volume type, new logic
    need to be introduced to convert LUN properties to provisioning type
    and tiering type used in volume type.
    Following changes are introduced as a side effect of this enhancement.
      * _Enum class is extraced from VNXError as a base class for
        enumerations.
      * Privisioning type and tiering type are converted to enum.
      * More properties need to be retrieved from array to check the type.
        Following changes are introduced by this change:
          * Seperate resource property descripters to individual class
            so that they are better organized.
          * Remove common matchers from property descripter to reduce the
            possibility of error.
          * Enhance the output parsing framework and assemble the logic in
            VNXCliParser class.
          * Create helper class Dict to allow access of properties with dot.
  * Reuse the logic in retype API when LUN type and volume type doesn't match.
  * Add API level unit test for the retype logic.
  * Add unit test for all refactored code.

Closes-Bug: #1480851:
Change-Id: I1de604124f9896ac4762854853a6215020a459d9

commit_message:
Add retype logic in manage_existing for VNX

The manage existing API for VNX driver didn't check the volume type.
Add type check and retype the volume if it's not match.
Raise ManageExistingVolumeTypeMismatch if volume type cannot be
satisfied.

Details of the change:

  * In order to compare the type of the LUN and the volume type, new
    logic need to be introduced to convert LUN properties to
    provisioning type and tiering type used in volume type.  Following
    changes are introduced as a side effect of this enhancement.
      * _Enum class is extracted from VNXError as a base class for
        enumerations.
      * Provisioning type and tiering type are converted to enum.
      * More properties need to be retrieved from array to check the
        type.
        Following changes are introduced by this change:
          * Separate resource property descriptors to individual class
            so that they are better organized.
          * Remove common matchers from property descriptor to reduce
            the possibility of error.
          * Enhance the output parsing framework and assemble the logic
            in VNXCliParser class.
          * Create helper class Dict to allow access of properties with
            dot.
  * Reuse the logic in retype API when LUN type and volume type doesn't
    match.
  * Add API level unit tests for the retype logic.
  * Add unit tests for all refactoring.

Closes-Bug: #1480851
Change-Id: I1de604124f9896ac4762854853a6215020a459d9

commit_message:
Allow customization of db sync command line

Add parameter to cinder::db::sync class to allow
end users to add command line parameters to the db sync command.

Change-Id: I34d9de89aae007d6b9f8644a8ba936bc0cf0c04c
Partial-bug: #1472740

[{'created': '2015-11-06 15:03:33.000000000', 'message': 'Optimize delete_csnat_router_interface_ports db query

Currently delete_csnat_router_interface_ports provides an iterator as
filter to core_plugin.get_ports which is used in a SQL IN argument.
SQLAlchemy is able to avoid some db queries when the IN argument is
empty BUT not when the argument is an empty iterator and raises the
warning:

 SAWarning: The IN-predicate on "ports.id" was invoked with an empty
 sequence. This results in a contradiction, which nonetheless can be
 expensive to evaluate. Consider alternative strategies for improved
 performance.

This change replaces the iterator by a list in order to optimize db
queries when the filter is empty.

Closes-Bug: #1503852
Change-Id: I4f53433d688dfa020927118a18020b1a6aa55517
(cherry picked from commit d5f3d59daf38035ced725be55931cb89ec1ccbcf)
'}]
commit_message:
Optimize delete_csnat_router_interface_ports db query

Currently delete_csnat_router_interface_ports provides an iterator as
filter to core_plugin.get_ports which is used in a SQL IN argument.
SQLAlchemy is able to avoid some db queries when the IN argument is
empty BUT not when the argument is an empty iterator and raises the
warning:

 SAWarning: The IN-predicate on "ports.id" was invoked with an empty
 sequence. This results in a contradiction, which nonetheless can be
 expensive to evaluate. Consider alternative strategies for improved
 performance.

This change replaces the iterator by a list in order to optimize db
queries when the filter is empty.

Closes-Bug: #1503852
Change-Id: I4f53433d688dfa020927118a18020b1a6aa55517
(cherry picked from commit d5f3d59daf38035ced725be55931cb89ec1ccbcf)

commit_message:
Don't remove ip addresses if not master

When setting --admin-state-up=False on an HA router with a gateway set,
standby nodes don't have any ip addresses set on the devices (although
the devices themselves are present). In such cases, Neutron should not
try to un-set those ip addresses before deleting the device itself.

Closes-bug: #1505203
Change-Id: I5df04b2ed1dc08286f6c467111c61c7f97643d66
(cherry picked from commit b8f17bac76171993d6d276c51264fea8becb6136)

remove default Neutron Network and Tunnel types

instead default to the default in tripleo-heat-templates.
tripleo-heat-templates default is set in
If57c79a1309ae178b3e82d54bb101dde584c86cc

Related:  rhbz#1244864

commit_message:
Add ability to selectively run ansible tests

Now that the Ansible module tests can be run via tox, it
might be nice to allow developers the ability to selectively
run individual module tests (accomplished via Ansible tags) from
tox.

Change-Id: I38a3040a7157a9bcf1cda76e26ab11577e9f80a6

commit_message:
honor the rabbit user and password provided

Currently rabbit username and password are defaulted and attempting
to use anything else would result in a failure during deployment.

Change-Id: I8a2e240a19f915309eee45ea3c3368d131af6c1b
Related:  rhbz#1261303

commit_message:
Use trueorfalse for OVN_L3_MODE.

devstack includes a function to handle boolean config values.  Use it
here.

Change-Id: I7d761f4283bf37ab7464398fa36d47f9fbbfa89c
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Add LeftHand volume manage and unmanage support

The config reference guide was missing the manage and unmanage support
for the LeftHand driver. This feature was added in the Kilo release,
but we neglected to update the documentation.

See review https://review.openstack.org/#/c/155127/ for details.

Change-Id: I4facf701604872a7bcbfbfc0ec16a08d6107513e

commit_message:
EMC VNX Manila Driver Refactoring

EMC VNX Manila driver refactoring targets to the following aspects:
1. Make the object-oriented storage object
2. Improve the unit test coverage

Change-Id: Ifbcad18fc00f9ed0d4f04efead30e8357d88a29f
Implements: blueprint emc-vnx-manila-driver-refactoring

commit_message:
Override 'enabled_backends' to None

When running a unit test on a system that already has devstack
installed or /etc/cinder/cinder.conf exists, test cases to fail.
This is happening because these test cases are expecting to have no
backends available, but cinder.conf provides backends by default.
This patch fixes this issue by overriding 'enabled_backends' to None.

Change-Id: I17da7dd6e422d508ccfe23cfe357ed2d4a1f9c88
Closes-Bug: #1498148

commit_message:
Properly wrap unplug errors

When an unplug_vif error occurs, it needs to be wrapped in a
NovaException so that the manager takes the right action.  This change
set properly wraps errors in the unplug_vifs.

Change-Id: I53928b80ec6d38063194ad06e3c89784bb8365ca
Closes-Bug: 1514437

Unfortunately, this solves only part of the problem: indeed, there is no more iscsi session on the host machine left. Still, if you check `virsh dumpxml` output, the volume is still there (despite, what both Nova and Cinder think).

This can be easily reproduce in the following way:

1. Start a new instance.
2. Attach a volume to the instance.
3. Stop the instance (nova stop $inst)
4. Start the instance and immediately detach the volume multiple times (nova start demo && nova volume-detach $inst $vol_id || nova volume-detach $inst $vol_id || nova volume-detach $inst $vol_id || nova volume-detach $inst $vol_id) <-- this is needed, because nova-api won't allow you to detach a volume in the BUILDING state.

Looks like an instance that just become ACTIVE still can't process detach properly: virDomainDetachFlags succeeds, but the device is still there. Curiously, if you try to that call multiple times, virDomainDetachFlags will fail with `can't find target dev vdb`, but it's still there in the virsh dumpxml output.

My current understanding is that this particular problem is somewhere in between of libvirt and qemu. We just need to figure out the root cause and understand how to work around this properly on Nova side..."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-09 20:30:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-04-17 22:03:59.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: Handle mismatch of volume information between BDM and domain XML

There is a case that the volume information is deleted from BDM
but the information remains on domain XML of Libvirt when user
detaches a volume from an instance if OS is hang up and so on.
If the volume is attached via iSCSI, currently iSCSI connection
is not disconnected even if the volume is detached because the
volume information exists on the domain XML.
After the instance will be rebooted, the domain XML is updated
to latest status and the volume information is removed,
therefore we should disconnect the iSCSI connection at the
volume detach sequence. This patch checks device list from
domain XML and remove detached device from the list.

Also additional volume attachment to the instance is failed
until instance will be rebooted. To avoid this issue, this
patch adds get_instance_disk_devices() to retrieve all disk
devices from domain XML and adds these devices to used drive
letter.

Closes-bug: #1374508
Change-Id: Id3034729c375573c96dea8c146c187e2bae0a193
'}, {'created': '2015-05-29 23:03:31.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: Handle mismatch of volume information between BDM and domain XML

commit_message:
libvirt: Handle mismatch of volume information between BDM and domain XML

There is a case that the volume information is deleted from BDM
but the information remains on domain XML of Libvirt when user
detaches a volume from an instance if OS is hang up and so on.
If the volume is attached via iSCSI, currently iSCSI connection
is not disconnected even if the volume is detached because the
volume information exists on the domain XML.
After the instance will be rebooted, the domain XML is updated
to latest status and the volume information is removed,
therefore we should disconnect the iSCSI connection at the
volume detach sequence. This patch checks device list from
domain XML and remove detached device from the list.

Also additional volume attachment to the instance is failed
until instance will be rebooted. To avoid this issue, this
patch adds get_instance_disk_devices() to retrieve all disk
devices from domain XML and adds these devices to used drive
letter.

DocImpact

Closes-bug: #1374508
Change-Id: Id3034729c375573c96dea8c146c187e2bae0a193

commit_message:
Fix Internal Server Error when query isn't specified

When calling search api, if 'query' is not specified with
'all_projects': true, an Internal Server Error will be raised.

Change-Id: I81497d4f7ea480f499ccf0ece06f0ef19536370f
Closes-bug: #1514738

commit_message:
Raise error if bad WWPNs used on connect

Raises an error if the connect volume is unable to find the appropriate
Virtual I/O Server for a WWPN.  This wraps into a proper Volume Attach
exception, so that the manager can handle the task state properly.

Change-Id: I6c98d0eb234a0e159907f68f8bd4b78255c90052
Closes-Bug: 1515357

Add common client constructor args

All client constructors need these. There is no reason to have them
be specific to client libs.

Change-Id: I1934cb086f905850941c06e0e79189f7642652d6

commit_message:
Deployment fix when container_networks are not set

The change updates the logic within nova such to it will
now correctly set the management interface when using
a dynamic inventory without the container_networks options
within it.

This also updates the container create play so that it too
will properly skip a host that also may not have the container
networks entries within it's inventory configs.

Change-Id: I157a6ecd0ad99000369d786a649c7b40d791d917
Closes-Bug: #1508517
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit aef4e7a891fac8c54bb0996aab825b48eb095f26)

[{'created': '2015-07-08 23:03:57.000000000', 'message': "WIP: Add new Connector APIs for path validation

This is a Work In Progress

The pupose of this patch is to look at adding new APIs to
os-brick Connector objects to see how we can help validate
discovered volumes.  By adding a few new APIs into the Connectors,
we can ask the Connector objects to give us a list of paths on
the system that are associated with a volume.  Then after doing
a disconnect, which happens during nova live migration as well as
normal volume detaches, we can fetch the list of all volumes, and
make sure the original volume paths don't exist in the list of all
volumes for that type.  Therefore verifying that when a volume
is removed, it doesn't leave any paths on the system behind.

TODO:
  * Get buyoff on the concept and APIs. probably needs a cinder-spec?
  * Figure out how to handle the new APIs for the vendor specific
    Connectors.
  * write a BP
  * Add unit tests

Change-Id: Ibf73545d81797ffeedd7d4bf10c6d11c63fce923

"}, {'created': '2015-08-28 15:30:33.000000000', 'message': "Add new Connector APIs for path validation

The purpose of this patch is to add new APIs to os-brick Connector objects
to see how we can help validate the discovered volumes.  By adding a few
new APIs into the Connectors, we can ask the Connector objects to give us
a list of paths on the system that are associated with a volume.
Then after doing a disconnect, which happens during nova live migration
as well as normal volume detaches, we can fetch the list of all volumes, and
make sure the original volume paths don't exist in the list of all
volumes for that type.  Therefore verifying that when a volume
is removed, it doesn't leave any paths on the system behind.

This patch adds the following new APIs to the Connector objects:
 * get_volume_paths() - fetch a list of paths on the system for a volume.
 * get_search_path() - get the path on the host where the Connector looks for
                       volumes.
 * get_all_available_volumes() - Get the entire list of volumes in the search
                                 path for the given protocol type (iSCSI, FC)

TODO:
  * cinded-spec needs approval

Implements: blueprint brick-fetch-paths
Change-Id: Ibf73545d81797ffeedd7d4bf10c6d11c63fce923

commit_message:
Add new Connector APIs for path validation

The purpose of this patch is to add new APIs to os-brick Connector objects
to see how we can help validate the discovered volumes.  By adding a few
new APIs into the Connectors, we can ask the Connector objects to give us
a list of paths on the system that are associated with a volume.
Then after doing a disconnect, which happens during nova live migration
as well as normal volume detaches, we can fetch the list of all volumes, and
make sure the original volume paths don't exist in the list of all
volumes for that type.  Therefore verifying that when a volume
is removed, it doesn't leave any paths on the system behind.

This patch adds the following new APIs to the Connector objects:
 * get_volume_paths() - fetch a list of paths on the system for a volume.
 * get_search_path() - get the path on the host where the Connector looks for
                       volumes.
 * get_all_available_volumes() - Get the entire list of volumes in the search
                                 path for the given protocol type (iSCSI, FC)

Cinder Spec:
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/204180/

Implements: blueprint brick-fetch-paths
Change-Id: Ibf73545d81797ffeedd7d4bf10c6d11c63fce923

commit_message:
Handle situation when endpoint deleted

when the cinder services exist but endpoint deleted, accessing
to /project/access_and_security will cause an error:
IndexError: list index out of range

Change-Id: Iad7f72cd5247f33245f25a8092c40a4d3a04cef9
Partial-Bug: #1394900
(cherry picked from commit 7985cfce77975d25ec6615b94f98ad920e727f93)

commit_message:
Silently drop access to non-existent flavours

Although not ideal, users are merely confused, when an error
message pops up, but everything works.

Change-Id: I765a8ba361e47e5a0af91328865db2515e51606a
Closes-bug: #1441523
(cherry picked from commit 8c8b130722e3b834fa3f334164c833e0b21f2c82)

commit_message:
Always fetch temp URL key before generation

SwiftClientPlugin.get_temp_url has the potential to race with
itself when storing a new tempurl key to the swift account,
leading to tempurls being built with a key that has been
overridden.

This change always fetches the key from swift before creating a
temp URL.

Change-Id: Id5897fdd834cc5d3b74fda8d2317d084a5564c51
Closes-Bug: #1413366

commit_message:
Provide locking around NPIV wwpns method

If the user runs two attach volumes at the same time, this can lead to a
race condition where different WWPNs get generated for the instance.
This change provides a lock around the wwpns call.  This is a global
lock for the compute node.

In previous iterations of this code, it could have had a major
performance impact.  But now that the job is invoked for the WWPNs call,
this method should return very quickly (subsecond).  Therefore the
global lock should not be a concern.

Change-Id: I4100e5c66797eb4f1fad802a88ef90966a05ce13
Closes-Bug: 1514537

commit_message:
Use correct mock assert call

assert_calls() doesn't exist and so this check was incorrectly always passing.

Update to assert_any_call(() to assert that _gettextutils.install('blaa')
with lookup BLAA_LOCALEDIR and potentially other environment vars.

Change-Id: Idef16696e65060282269315978ca6f0cc01fafe9

commit_message:
switch partial upgrade testing to multinode

Grenade multinode testing is now as stable as the partial-ncpu job,
and is far less synthetic for upgrade purposes. This should be made
voting, and partial-ncpu no longer run in master.

Test results comparisons can be seen here: http://tinyurl.com/p6l4lvd

Change-Id: I086eedc05e4bd6e5ac829e337fc06117861e3ff2

commit_message:
Expose stack_user_project_id in stack-show

stack_user_project_id is currently never exposed by heat, so the user
has no way of discovering what it is.

This has a couple of implications:
- The user can't call the REST API create_software_deployment unless
  they know the stack_user_project_id of the stack that the server
  resource belongs to
- user can't do manual cleanup of stack_user_project_id when necessary

This change adds stack_user_project_id to the formatted output of
the stack-show REST API call.

Change-Id: I0a2d337401c164eb58dbce63e01f68f98f8d467e
Closes-Bug: #1413398

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-01 18:54:00.000000000', 'message': 'Correct the status change time
Closes-Bug: 1286379
Author: Petra Sargent
Date: Sun November 1 2015

Correct the status change time

This fix corrects the status change time. The intent is to wait
until the status of the datastore service/app changes to the
passed in value. The _get_actual_db_status is invoked repeatedly
every 3 seconds until the passed in status is observed or time
out occurs (whichever happens first).  The bug is in the way the
waited_time is accumulated inside the loop. It incremented by 3
for every loop iteration withough giving consideration to how long
the _get_actual_db_status() call might take before returning.
The fix calculates how much time it takes for _get_actual_db_status
takes before returning and adds the time to the waited_time to
more accurately reflect the time elapsed.

I would like to request feedback on how to test the fix while I
make by attempts.

Change-Id: Ibdeb94f30fee9d4337ec5095794466a61caf09ad
'}, {'created': '2015-11-02 00:07:48.000000000', 'message': 'Correct the status change time
Closes-Bug: 1286379
Author: Petra Sargent
Date: Sun November 1 2015

Correct the status change time

This fix corrects the status change time. The intent is to wait
until the status of the datastore service/app changes to the
passed in value. The _get_actual_db_status is invoked repeatedly
every 3 seconds until the passed in status is observed or time
out occurs (whichever happens first).  The bug is in the way the
waited_time is accumulated inside the loop. It incremented by 3
for every loop iteration withough giving consideration to how long
the _get_actual_db_status() call might take before returning.
The fix calculates how much time it takes for _get_actual_db_status
takes before returning and adds the time to the waited_time to
more accurately reflect the time elapsed.

This fix corrects the status change time. The intent is to wait
until the status of the datastore service/app changes to the
passed in value. The _get_actual_db_status is invoked repeatedly
every 3 seconds until the passed in status is observed or time
out occurs (whichever happens first).  The bug is in the way the
waited_time is accumulated inside the loop. It incremented by 3
for every loop iteration withough giving consideration to how long
the _get_actual_db_status() call might take before returning.
The fix calculates how much time it takes for _get_actual_db_status
takes before returning and adds the time to the waited_time to
more accurately reflect the time elapsed.

I would like to request feedback on how to test the fix while I
make by attempts.

The change(s) to test_dbaas (the tests) are because of an unfortunate
side-effect of the old code. The tests would just mock() sleep() but
the old code would advice the amount of time waited by whatever time
they thought they'd have waited for. This meant that the
wait_for_real_status_to_change_to method would take approximately no
time in tests but would appear to do all the right things. However,
since the new code is using time.time() to deterime how long it's been
around has caused the mock'ing of sleep() to have an unexpected
result; the wait_for_real_status_to_change_to method becomes a CPU
hog! The hack I've used is to fake time with a side_effect that
advances at 1 'second' per call.
