commit_message:
Correct the computation of elapsed time while waiting for state change

The computation of elapsed time and present time during waiting for
state change is incorrect. This change simplifies the code and
corrects that error.

There is a subtle change in behavior also introduced as part of this
change. Earlier code would unconditionally wait for WAIT_TIME before
checking status. The proposed code will immediately poll status.

A configuration parameter has been added for the WAIT_TIME with the
former default value of 3.

The change(s) to test_dbaas (the tests) are because of an unfortunate
side-effect of the old code. The tests would just mock sleep() but
the old code would advance the amount of time waited by whatever time
they thought they'd have waited for. This meant that the
wait_for_real_status_to_change_to method would take approximately no
time in tests but would appear to do all the right things. However,
since the new code is using time.time() to deterime how long it's been
around has caused the mock'ing of sleep() to have an unexpected
result; the wait_for_real_status_to_change_to method becomes a CPU
hog! The hack I've used is to fake time with a side_effect that
advances at 1 'second' per call.

Closes-Bug: #1286379
Closes-Bug: #1514991
Change-Id: Ibdeb94f30fee9d4337ec5095794466a61caf09ad
Co-Authored-By: Amrith Kumar <amrith@tesora.com>
Author:    Petra Sargent <petra_sargent@yahoo.com>

commit_message:
Raise upper bound on django_openstack_auth <1.2.0

A new release of django_openstack_auth(DOA) is needed to include the
current capped requirements specifically oslo.config:
 $ git grep oslo 1.1.9:requirements.txt
 1.1.9:requirements.txt:6:oslo.config>=1.6.0  # Apache-2.0

This measn that olso.config 2.X is being installed which no longer
contains the olso namespace,

In order to accommodate this raise the acceptable maximum to anything in
the 1.1.x series, keeping the block on 1.1.8.

Change-Id: Ife07c09009ab1bcb7229ad9e8d0527406f4f61c9
Related-Bug: 1497819

Yes. We would like to use kolla-ansible in for the similar things like in kolla. It means - creating/migrating database, creating users/domains/roles in OpenStack. I got a question here.  It was mentioned that the ansible bits of kolla might become kolla-ansible at some point after kolla-mesos lands.  Are we sure we want to be combining the two? (1 comment)

@Ryan: The kolla-ansible container is separate thing from the whole ansible/ directory, so I think that we can

- change only ansible/ dir into kolla-ansible project in future
- keep kolla-ansible dockerfile in kolla and use it in both kolla-ansible and kolla-mesos

Generally, kolla-ansible mostly creates things related with database, keystone etc. We would like to reuse it in kolla-mesos too, as a container runned by Chronos.'}, {'account_id': 10419, 'date': '2015-11-13 15:31:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Add ZooKeeper support in kolla-ansible

In kolla-mesos, ZK will be used for storing information about
actions done in bootstrap.

Change-Id: Id7067a493b457cf7b73eb007852df7b13f4363b3
Partially-Implements: blueprint zookeeper

Comment 'recheck-netapp-ci' to rerun these tests. https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/ThirdPartySystems/NetApp_CI"}, {'account_id': 2101, 'date': '2015-08-27 15:24:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi John, thanks for your comments.  I'll try and make my case briefly.

We currently have customers running Juno and soon adopting Kilo.  In cases where the users have adopted the keystone v3 functionality around domains we have a case where there is the concept of a 'cloud global admin' and a 'domain level admin'.

The concern is the domain level admin can add users to their domain and can assign roles to those users (and themselves).

The check_is_admin function currently sets a 'global admin' status that allows users that pass that check to view/manage all volumes regardless of tenant.

Without the patch any user that is granted role:admin can perform these global cloud level functions for cinder.  With the patch, administrators can set the RBAC check in cinder/policy.json to 'context_is_admin': 'user_id: <user guid>' which will restrict global functions to that user_id.

Without the patch, user_id cannot be considered.  The ability to consider items other than role is currently mixed across projects, but all other projects offer at least some functionality to restrict based on something other than role.  This patch gives us parity there.

I called it a tactical fix because it is less than ideal, as other factors like domain_id + role would be a better fit and simpler to maintian.  However getting domain_id into the context properly would have been a larger change and a bigger risk, so I left that off, believing that the entire concept of admin scoping was being reworked and that when completed that would take care of these concerns."}, {'account_id': 17718, 'date': '2015-08-29 07:57:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
adds user_id to check_is_admin

A small tactical update to allow cinder to consider user_id
when checking for admin.

This is needed in the field until the larger changes around
admin scoping are completed. Checking for role only is not
sufficient in a multi-domain configuration.

juno-backport-potential
kilo-backport-potential

closes-bug: 968696

Change-Id: I0cb99186bd833c4c32964490c4bc6da9ad42d320
(cherry picked from commit 9840721b51671296816d681dbd4b9afe221f68b4)

[{'created': '2015-08-14 18:49:17.000000000', 'message': 'Add retry for tgtadm update when tgt exists

For target creation using tgtadm driver, we create a persistence
file for the target, then send a tgt-admin --update 'name' where
name is the specific persistence file we want to read in and update
from.

It turns out that we can hit race conditions where the persistence
file is written, and an update is requested but target has already
done work to make it believe that the target has already been created.

One thought was to just use "update ALL" but this still seems to have
issues, and changes the error to an account exists failure.

This patch takes the brute force approach and adds a retry to the
update command.

NOTE this patch was originally applied Kilo:

But this couldn't be directly cherry-picked due to the use of
an external retry library.  This patch takes the same approach
but uses a simple loop around the udpate call.

Change-Id: Ia23b3a5a5a7c28e054f795c46acd5f6a8e63c823
Closes-Bug: #1398078
'}]
commit_message:
Add retry for tgtadm update when tgt exists

For target creation using tgtadm driver, we create a persistence
file for the target, then send a tgt-admin --update 'name' where
name is the specific persistence file we want to read in and update
from.

It turns out that we can hit race conditions where the persistence
file is written, and an update is requested but target has already
done work to make it believe that the target has already been created.

One thought was to just use "update ALL" but this still seems to have
issues, and changes the error to an account exists failure.

This patch takes the brute force approach and adds a retry to the
update command.

NOTE this patch was originally applied Kilo:
Ic72fb5f4fca70a7e7d1c306efe19674fd7e42cd6

But this couldn't be directly cherry-picked due to the use of
an external retry library.  This patch takes the same approach
but uses a simple loop around the udpate call.
Please see lp entry for details.

Change-Id: Ia23b3a5a5a7c28e054f795c46acd5f6a8e63c823
Closes-Bug: #1398078

commit_message:
Fixes bug in deletion of a non existing volume

If a non existing volume is deleted the NetApp
iSCSI eseries driver throws a NetAppDriverException
in the delete_volume method.
This situation can occurr if the user manually deletes
a LUN in the NetApp controller directly or if the
delete operation initiated via cinder is interrupted,
which leaves the system in an inconsistent state.
For example if the volume is deleted on the NetApp
controller but still residing in the OpenStack database.

Change-Id: Ib41fbd089a4e39cd81477e3b932a5346a07e6736
Closes-Bug: #1477027

commit_message:
Disable voting for pep8 job on stable branches of fuel-web repo

To fix merge locks for stable branches which were generated
by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/240440/

commit_message:
Require tox >= 2.0

We use passenv in the file, and as per [1], it's introduced in tox 2.0.

[1] https://testrun.org/tox/latest/config.html#confval-passenv=SPACE-SEPARATED-GLOBNAMES

commit_message:
Harden Material Theme

A recent change fixed the sidebar height of the default theme but introduced
a bug in the Large screen of the Material Design theme.

It was also noted, while fixing this bug, that old styles were also
preventing webkit checkbox customizing properly on Chrome.

Change-Id: I5809037d336e401611614d0c7b2e0569a1f4c07a
Closes-Bug: #1508692

commit_message:
Separate agents tests from networks tests file

This patch separates the Agents tests from the Networks tests file due
to file bloat. Previously, this file contained tests for Networks,
Subnets, Ports and DHCP Agents.

Also added missing copyright back to Ports tests

Change-Id: I61075c4b1bddb774046eac6eb11509d2edca3fc2
Closes-Bug: 1514048

commit_message:
NetApp: Fix issue with updating E-Series password

The NetApp E-Series storage array password is specified in the
configuration file, and must be updated if the array has its password
changed via the management software. However, the logic to check
whether or not the password is currently valid was incorrect, and
was not correctly detecting an invalid password in need of updating.

This patch fixes the password validity checking for the driver,
refactors the existing code to be more concise, and adds additional
unittests around this functionality.

Change-Id: I1468d1810479947a9cff7ef8b79440de4063cbed
Closes-Bug: #1497007

[{'created': '2015-10-19 13:59:15.000000000', 'message': "Added CORS support to Nova

This adds the CORS support middleware to Nova, allowing a deployer
to optionally configure rules under which a javascript client may
break the single-origin policy and access the API directly. Included
are Nova's custom headers, so that anyone activating this
middleware does not have to explicitly enable them.

The paste.ini method of deploying the middleware was
chosen, because it needs to be able to annotate responses created
by keystonemiddleware. If the middleware were explicitly included
as in the previous patch, keystone would reject the request before
the cross-domain headers could be annotated, resulting in an
error response that was unreadable by the user agent.

OpenStack CrossProject Spec:
   http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/openstack-specs/specs/cors-support.html
Oslo_Middleware Docs:
   http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.middleware/cors.html
OpenStack Cloud Admin Guide:
   http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/cross_project_cors.html

commit_message:
Added CORS support to Nova

This adds the CORS support middleware to Nova, allowing a deployer
to optionally configure rules under which a javascript client may
break the single-origin policy and access the API directly.

The paste.ini method of deploying the middleware was
chosen, because it needs to be able to annotate responses created
by keystonemiddleware. If the middleware were explicitly included,
keystone would reject the request before the cross-domain headers
could be annotated, resulting in an error response that was
unreadable by the user agent.

The test suite was expanded, to permit the inclusion of
HTTP headers, and to add the ability to send an OPTIONS request.

OpenStack CrossProject Spec:
   http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/openstack-specs/specs/cors-support.html
Oslo_Middleware Docs:
   http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.middleware/cors.html
OpenStack Cloud Admin Guide:
   http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/cross_project_cors.html

bp:nova-cors 
Change-Id: Ibc95df0860799ff36f682da7d032d5422b0c39c1

When I deploy director with NFS backend for cinder,
sometimes I don't need nfs mount options.
If I choose to omit this option, or if the option
is defined to '', the deployment fails.

This patch add just a default value for this option.

commit_message:
Fix cinder error when CinderNfsMountOptions option is absent

When I deploy director with NFS backend for cinder,
sometimes I don't need nfs mount options.
If I choose to omit this option, or if the option
is defined to '', the deployment fails.

This patch add just a default value for this option.

Change-Id: Idf708aaecebd5c6db14f48ad2a53d6c2453be5ee
Bugzilla: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1281870

within it.

This also updates the container create play so that it too
will properly skip a host that also may not have the container

commit_message:
Deployment fix when container_networks are not set

The change updates the logic within nova such to it will
now correctly set the management interface when using
a dynamic inventory without the container_networks options
within it.

This also updates the container create play so that it too
will properly skip a host that also may not have the container
networks entries within it's inventory configs.

Change-Id: I157a6ecd0ad99000369d786a649c7b40d791d917
Closes-Bug: #1508517
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>
(cherry picked from commit aef4e7a891fac8c54bb0996aab825b48eb095f26)

commit_message:
Fixing a simple issue in results count to fix exit code

This commit fixes a simple mistake in the baseline code that was
causing a baseline run with no new issues to return a fail.

Basically we were deleting all objects from the baseline list, and
then using the length of the baseline list to check if we were in
baseline mode.  Since the length was now 0, we decided we weren't
running baseline.

Now we make a copy of the list and delete issues from the copy to
leave the original list alone.  Also we make the code more clear
by doing an explicit list of get_issue_list instead of length
of filter().

Change-Id: I32af0a1291cb94a527f31f4fcfe8faa7be302095

commit_message:
Updates Swarm Heat Templates for Container Network Model

Previously, the swarm bay type did not support the Magnum
Container Networking Model (CNM). This patch adds support for
CNM through the following:

1. Refactors swarm templates to better align with k8s templates.
2. Adds network-driver, labels, master/node flavors and
docker_vol_size to swarm bay type.
3. Updates swarm functional tests to support CNM changes.

Partially-Implements: blueprint extend-baymodel-net-attributes
Partially-Implements: blueprint conductor-template-net-update
Partially-Implements: blueprint heat-network-refactor

Change-Id: I7cb90748b5f668f79a8e5a9079272eff14db34ce

commit_message:
make devstack testing doc a bit more clear on host name

devstack testing doc uses two nodes for demoing how ovn work, in
the doc it was not very clear that two nodes need to have different
host names. Since developers often clone VMs so the host names are
normaly the same, this actually cuases problems in this exercise.
This patch set will add few lines to make sure developers use
different host names for the two VMs.

Change-Id: Ie29f17e1aa74f58079a3085bce9c657dfc6e5d26
Closes-bug: #1516068

commit_message:
Only use GET_PIP_URL when it is set

The logic in scripts/scripts-library.sh was recently changed with
respect to installing pip, however the conditional wasn't updated to
only use GET_PIP_URL when it is set.  This simple commits flips the
if statement to use a '-n' (checking if GET_PIP_URL is non-empty
instead) of a '-z'.

Change-Id: I6ace12f183e944a6cee2d7ab722424152f5eb419

use project_id rather than tenant_id in the filter sent to the API.

feature and based on the previous feedback, I have made use of mock
instead of stub.

commit_message:
Add test for snapshot filtering by project id

Cinder API already supports listing snapshots by project id. But a
test case is missing to validate this feature. Hence added that in
this patch.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/242391/ --> adds this support on the
python-cinderclient side.

Change-Id: I70606abf2fe5eca43cd0a3d15f7b9e12bb979b3b
Co-Authored-By: wuyuting <wytdahu@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Refacter Endpoints into EndpointMap

Because many of the service endpoints URLs use the same patterns for
generating the URLs it makes sense to use the same templates to reduce
the copy and paste.

In the process also adds support for explicitly specifying hostnames
for use in the endpoints.  Note: DNS must be pre-configured.   The
Heat templates do not directly configure DNS.

Change-Id: Ie3270909beca3d63f2d7e4bcb04c559380ddc54d
Co-Authored-By: Juan Antonio Osorio Robles <jaosorior@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Revert "Fix ironic driver for Liberty release"

ironic-fa-deploy rpm package requires ironic-conductor. 
So this ironic-conductor must be available either 
on MOS or upstream mirrors. As far as openstack 
rpm packages are not a part of MOS 8.0 we need 
to remove rpm spec for ironic-fa-deploy package. 
Otherwise, ISO can not be built with BUILD_PACKAGES=0. 

This reverts commit 52b5b8de280717e457e0db464aa62e540461c180.

Change-Id: I021a6fb5c544e17ac29cf231f1a233c9b09645dc

commit_message:
Fix dnsmasq restart requiring sudo privileges

The task will fail, as sending a HUP signal requires sudo.

Change-Id: I40ed4fbc0bc5c4db96afd58566fcdf0d55e60c44
Closes-Bug: lp1514747

[{'created': '2015-11-11 22:49:04.000000000', 'message': "Add DeployIdentifier overcloud parameter

We've heard from end users that it is confusing that puppet
isn't re-executed on a heat stack-update.

This patch adds a new DeployIdentifier parameter which
we can set via client tooling (tripleoclient) to a unique
value so that on each heat stack-update we always execute
all of our configuration deployments.

Change-Id: Ic352ddd30807dc378e5e7b6c396bc53f5d6d5622
Related-bug: #1505430
"}]
commit_message:
Add DeployIdentifier overcloud parameter

We've heard from end users that it is confusing that puppet
isn't re-executed on a heat stack-update.

This patch adds a new DeployIdentifier parameter which
we can set via client tooling (tripleoclient) to a unique
value so that on each heat stack-update we always execute
all of our configuration deployments.

Change-Id: Ic352ddd30807dc378e5e7b6c396bc53f5d6d5622
Related-bug: #1505430

commit_message:
Delete old stacks on successful app deploy

This change is to delete all the old heat stacks on successful
new workflow deployment(if new workflow is in READY state).
Below given are the changes;
1. Saving app uuid as plan uuid
2. Using assembly plan_id to get the app_id
3. Based on the app_id getting all the old assemblies
   of the given app and deleting the heat stacks

Change-Id: If5fad35c218c07b6320b8564d41571634c1ee4cd
Closes-Bug: #1514605

[{'account_id': 9098, 'date': '2015-11-11 15:59:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:09:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

There should be unit tests.'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:11:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Also, I don't think this is backwards-compatible. If this was working for somebody and they had their normal groups working with non-member and enabled emulation working with this then now it will be broken.

commit_message:
Remove hardcoded LDAP group schema from emulated enabled mix-in

The emulated enabled mix-in uses hard-coded LDAP schema for the
group objectclass and membership attributes.  This patch makes the
mix-in optionally use the LDAP group configuration settings.

Change-Id: I5ed9d552ec140f83578398fd29e2130ebf827662
Closes-Bug: #1515302

commit_message:
Raise minimum oslo.messaging requirement

Release 2.6.0 changed the paths for the messaging notification
driver (see review 227374).  Neutron (and possibly others) imports these
drivers and needs to update their paths accordingly, and as such
requires a minimum here.  This removes all existing constraints and
adds a simple constraint of >2.6.1.

Change-Id: Ic2f24a5132ca6ea4277f29205feb12fd0ef14efb
Partial-bug: #1513630

commit_message:
Neutron: add internal & floating names to params

In order to remove internal and floating network names hardcoding from
Nailgun database, let's move them to neutron parameters. It'll simplify
support for developers, and allow user to change them as they want.

Change-Id: Ic0ca82047cb750609a5313c2eab02569b9633239
Partial-Bug: #1349702

commit_message:
Providing permission for swift to access ceilometer group

The default access setting for the /var/log/ceilometer,
directory is 740, which will not allow swift to add files
to that folder and hence swift-proxy will not restart.

Change-Id: I9b6ed615f0b16a42418bfdcf84c4144796174a30
Closes-Bug: #1511956

Also as i understood all these operations would have higher priority, if someone decide rename instance during live-migration for example, l-m should be paused, if possible, instance renamed, and l-m resumed. is it correct?'}, {'account_id': 1865, 'date': '2015-09-28 16:37:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Timofey the only problematic actions here are pause/unpause.
For the pause the idea proposed by @pawel is to add a new API call for pausing an instance during a live-migration, when this call is executed the instance get paused, once the live-migration is completed the instance is put back to the ACTIVE state. 
The unpause is still under discussion, it could be an action that we don't want to allow as it could lead to some potential race condition as Daniel Berrange reported in his review on the original specs: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/179346/1/specs/liberty/approved/enhance-instance-operations-during-live-migration.rst

The other actions are just nova operations so there is no need to pause the instance to perform them as they shouldn't interfere with the live-migration process.
Does that answer your questions?"}, {'account_id': 1865, 'date': '2015-09-30 14:32:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 1865, 'date': '2015-09-30 14:33:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

So I really am not sure about this spec.

It seems like an edge case, that will be really hard to maintain, for quite minimal gain.

I actually prefer the idea of implementing cancel this release, so folk can do things if they really need to:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/228828/

I vote we prove we have live-migrate rock solid before we consider adding this complexity.

I would want to know the detailed test strategy we are committing to before approving something like this.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-11-12 11:58:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

If we consider our overall goal is for live-migration to be invisible to the tenant users, then I think it is important to allow further operations where reasonable.

This spec covers a mixture of things - some which change VM state (eg reboot), which do add complexity to workflow, and some which just allow tenant access to info about the VM (eg log / console)

At the very least I think we really must allow access to the console & logs.

COuld we perhaps split this spec up, so that we have one spec for each feature we want to allow, so we can decide on approval individual, instead of blocking the entire thing.'}, {'account_id': 7461, 'date': '2015-11-12 13:53:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

Agree we should split this up. I will take it off the live migration subteam list and we can add new specs that we decide are in scope.'}, {'account_id': 1865, 'date': '2015-11-13 15:14:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

thanks all for your comments, I am going to split the specs in 3 different ones, so maybe we can decide to put some of them in scope for Mitaka'}, {'account_id': 1865, 'date': '2015-11-13 16:49:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

actually we need just one spec for the reboot soft action as the other actions are already allowed even if they need some changes, I am thinking for example to the console-log file which is not migrated with the instance, but that is a different topic.'}, {'account_id': 1865, 'date': '2015-11-13 16:49:19.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Allow more instance operations during live migration

This spec proposes a change to Nova to allow an operator
or user to perform more actions on an instance while it
is being live migrated. The actions are all ones which
exist in Nova already but are currently blocked.

APIImpact
blueprint enhance-instance-operations-during-live-migration
Change-Id: I05a293f5aa5818c43eacdabb6d443e270d84c2d0

commit_message:
Add tenant-id to subresources

When a tenant access a subresource, neutron will check that this
tenant is allowed to view this subresource, according to the policy.json.
The plugin must return the tenant_id parameter when a "show/list/delete"
action is performed, so that the policy framework can check authz.

This patch also set the network_id as a mandatory parameter
in the network_association table.

Change-Id: I59d2dbb5416b566dc7de3acb4fab3ed2ada8b78e
Fixes-Bug: #1512789

commit_message:
Augment token to indicate if it is scoped to the admin project

This will provide the ability for policy rules to more securely
allow access to privaleged operations.

Co-Authored-By: Henry Nash <henryn@linux.vnet.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Remove hardcoded utf8 coding for bgpvpns table

to align to the kilo code it is necessary to
let the database decide to use latin1 or utf8
as codec. Otherwise bgpvpn_network_associations
table cannot have foreign keys to networks
and bgpvpns. The reason is that for foreign keys
the column in the table and the column in the
foreign table has to have the same codec.

Change-Id: I2e732d8474f6769259e25d69b1b5269bebc9c26f
Closes-Bug: 1515987

commit_message:
Add backup metadata fields

Freezer now is able to store more metadata about the backups including:
  - log_file
  - storage
  - mode
  - os_auth_version
  - proxy
  - compression
  - ssh_key
  - ssh_username
  - ssh_host
  - ssh_port

Change-Id: If9df17315c738a2c048113955d9ab21b760b6f36

commit_message:
Enable translations

The infra scripts need the oslo.privsep/locale directory to exist,
so create it with an empty file in it. This way syncing to our
translation server of translation strings will work.

Change-Id: Ia73059aeaecefe7dc6937bb01c7f4338d6173abd

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-12 14:49:16.000000000', 'message': "Fix parameter_defaults for comma_delimited_list and json

When environment of a stack contained a parameter_defaults section with
a value for a parameter of type comma_delimited_list or json, that default
didn't get applied unless in a nested stack.

The issue was that CommaDelimitedListParam contains a variable to cache
its value, and that cache was only created upon creation of a
CommaDelimitedListParam object, but it wasn't updated on `set_default`
method call. The cache now updates on `set_default` too.

Conflicts:
	heat/engine/parameters.py

Co-Authored-By: Steven Hardy <shardy@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I85b13a79dbc97a77e20c0d5df8eaf05b3000815e
Closes-Bug: #1504137
(cherry picked from commit 3827c61b25fa86c1f9882be15caf27d2efa6c4fe)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix parameter_defaults for comma_delimited_list and json

When environment of a stack contained a parameter_defaults section with
a value for a parameter of type comma_delimited_list or json, that default
didn't get applied unless in a nested stack.

The issue was that CommaDelimitedListParam contains a variable to cache
its value, and that cache was only created upon creation of a
CommaDelimitedListParam object, but it wasn't updated on `set_default`
method call. The cache now updates on `set_default` too.

Conflicts:
	heat/engine/parameters.py

Co-Authored-By: Steven Hardy <shardy@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I85b13a79dbc97a77e20c0d5df8eaf05b3000815e
Closes-Bug: #1504137
(cherry picked from commit 3827c61b25fa86c1f9882be15caf27d2efa6c4fe)

commit_message:
Zero Downtime Reindexing Proposal

This patch provides the initial proposal for
zero downtime reindexing. Currently we don't
have a specs repo. It is intended that we use
this patch for discussion and the morph the rst
file in here into the final documentation for the feature.

See the parent patch for more information on the proposed workflow.

This is an experiment at doing a hybrid model of
spec repos for complex features with real time
documentation

Change-Id: I8d8a92c8d6c5596a7d45c34044950ffa2e9a7a75
Partially-Implements: blueprint zero-downtime-reindexing

commit_message:
Add LC_ALL=C to lvcreate, lvextend and pvresize

In various locales decimal mark is considered to be ',' instead of '.'.
This creates a problem when Cinder executes lvcreate, lvextend or
pvresize because it always passes numerals in 1.00g form and these
commands expect 1,00g when started with LC_NUMERIC set to one of such
locales. This commit adds LC_ALL=C env variable to all executions of
lvcreate, lvextends and pvresize and updates rootwrap's volume.filters
accordingly to make sure that parameters are interpreted in a correct
way.

Depends-On: Ie25194997b94664ec14a0f94d09c167f4fad3b4d
Change-Id: Ice7ae67f649f75cbbf2702f5f732d489ebe08aa8
Closes-Bug: 1488433

commit_message:
Add copying new rootwrap filters to Cinder upgrade

To fix bug 1488433 new rootwrap filters need to be created. This
commit adds copying of new volume.filters file to proper directory
to update rootwrap rules.

Related-Bug: 1488433

commit_message:
Providing permission for swift to access ceilometer group

The default access setting for the /var/log/ceilometer,
directory is 740,which will not allow swift to add file
to that folder and hence swift-proxy will not restart.

Change-Id: I78cf3d5364b4dd65d73e770007bdae8afcbed290
Closes-Bug: #1511956

commit_message:
Add call to pluggable IPAM from ml2 delete_subnet

ml2 plugin overrides delete_subnet and do not call super(),
so pluggable IPAM action defined in db_base_plugin_v2 are not called.
As a result subnets can not be deleted from IPAM driver if ml2 plugin
is used.

Added ipam.delete_subnet call into ml2 delete_subnet.
Patch includes UT to verify IPAM driver is called on subnet
allocation and deallocation.
Test class is inherited from TestMl2SubnetsV2, so all SubnetV2 tests are
additionally executed for ml2 plugin with reference IPAM driver.

Closes-Bug: #1510653

Change-Id: I2b7ddfe70a1275a141af38e18151e1fc000e2682
(cherry picked from commit 99573f62d1fc79a4308784ab2c799d836b7a3d74)

commit_message:
Correct errors resulting in "No handlers ..." error message

This is a checkin for the issue of having errors that read "No
handlers could be found for logger X.Y.Z" when running tests. While
being annoying, it is also a serious issue in that some times, the
lack of logging masks errors in the tests. One such example is fixed
in this chkin (see bug 1491093).

Change-Id: I4066d226aefbd23248e88692db109d31f5c150e9
Partial-Bug: #1491075
Closes-Bug: #1491093

commit_message:
add test to ensure cloud is using minimum number of nodes

This ensures that the the cloud in question is using some minimum
number of nodes as specified by compute.min_compute_nodes. We then
attempt to schedule to all those nodes directly with scheduler hints,
and verify that the host_ids are all different on the booted nodes.

This kind of test is needed when doing multinode rolling upgrade
testing, because an extremely common failure is a change which makes
the upgraded controller incompatible with a non upgraded worker. The
worker will then stop communicating and effectively drop out of the
cluster. All the other tests will pass because they just route around
the damage. However we really do want to poke every node to make sure
they all still work.

Change-Id: I7d7230d100901179a1d1a0281aa8be990d00c02a

commit_message:
Freezer-Scheduler port to Windows

added windows service to run freezer-scheduler in the background
updated README on how to use it in windows
fix portability issues for dealing with paths

commit_message:
Remove Null Data from Publisher

Monasca has added a check for null data. When the publisher does not
find the meter value or metadata it defaults it to Null.

This causes Monasca API to reject the sample. This is particularly
evident in the Central and Compute Agents since they collect data
that may be null.

Change-Id: I51ca07ec10c6b414b6a26c057edc09487053f982

commit_message:
Checks consistency of net association vs BGPVPN id

This change introduces checks so that on a GET for a
network association on a BGPVPN, the network association
is returned only if it is actually bound to this BGPVPN.

Change in:
- plugin/driver interface
- DB code, to detect inconsistency and raise an error
- test cases

Additionally, the code adapts DELETE codepath for the
same reason.

Change-Id: I71d9c4b0fc08975c40c8da3a67e1d5837f1b1f73
Closes-Bug: 1513087

commit_message:
Add new context manager for shade exceptions, final.

This commit completes the work of
 change Ic39b6e3efc33b7a30f298a3daca6d6c16ab4ca89

Shade has developed a common pattern within many of the API
methods where we try to avoid re-wrapping OpenStackClientException
exceptions by catching them and simply re-raising. We can eliminate
this duplicate exception handling with a context manager.

Change-Id: If236656146ecfa5a2b3eb3379efc6869829bdaa7

commit_message:
[zmq] Add config options to specify dynamic ports range

Operators may need a possibility to restrict ports ranges for a specified services
in order to distinguish ports related to zmq messaging from all other ports in a system.

Change-Id: Ibe5b02c1211b16859ff58bc02a59d96e1d2fa660
Closes-Bug: #1511181

commit_message:
Remove mysql_* statements in db creation script

There is no reason why yhe mysql_default_charset and mysql_engine statements
would be needed and this is actually creating issues.

Change-Id: I331749aa91b012ccdb6083819a56c7ef28642ddd
Closes-Bug: 1515987

The block_device_mapping list parameter is a BlockDeviceMappingList

information in the logs. Cast to a list to get the sub-objects repr'ed
in the logs.

commit_message:
Properly log BlockDeviceMappingList in _create_block_device_mapping

The block_device_mapping list parameter is a BlockDeviceMappingList
object, and list objects don't repr the sub-objects so it's useless
information in the logs. Cast to a list to get the sub-objects repr'ed
in the logs.

The bdm list of dicts from the API request is converted to a
BlockDeviceMappingList in _check_and_transform_bdm which is called from
_create_instance before _create_block_device_mapping.

Closes-Bug: #1513934

Change-Id: Id709c0bc9d0ad980d0b36973f3a52034003170af

There was a discussion on #openstack-oslo about what this review means. essentially anyone currently using zookeeper (monasca api and cue for example) and are *NOT* using dlm(s) are being asked to flip use_dlm to use this common code.

http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-oslo/%23openstack-oslo.2015-11-10.log.html#t2015-11-10T19:44:56

I am torn as i see both sides of the debate. i am abstaining from a vote :)'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2015-11-11 23:32:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

My worry here, and that I see discussed in some places but not really resolved, is that (dlm == zookeeper) seems correct -- devstack can be opinionated and say "if you're doing dlm work and you call use_dlm you're going to get zookeeper".  That said, obviously the whole idea of abstracting implementation behind a "dlm" alias is that you retain the possibility of switching it for something else.  The idea is that people are using tooz and shouldn't even really care what's underneath.  

But the reverse, (zookeeper == dlm) is not true.  There are examples of zookeeper being used for service discovery and coordination. So if these services call "use_dlm" just to get zookeeper (everyone has to coexist) we've just broken the whole point of the abstraction.

My suggestion would be to retain the zookeper service -- it seems like multiple projects want it so centralising install/setup of it is good -- and make the "dlm" service an alias to zookeeper.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-11-12 13:32:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

This is all just a terminology fight right? There is literally no code difference between this than the name.

If someone else has a better generic name than dlm for class of things here, lets use that. But we don't even call rabbit "messaging" in openstack, we call it rpc_backend. Even though it's used for notifications by as many things as rpc. 

I really think that zookeeper in devstack needs to always be behind an abstraction, or never be behind and abstraction, and we give up on the idea that tooz is our interface. This middle ground is just a mess for deployers and developers.

We blessed this as a thing in OpenStack you could depend on based on a specific abstraction for it.'}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2015-11-12 13:38:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

ok Sold! :)'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2015-11-12 22:09:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
refactor zookeeper into a slightly more generic dlm module

This attempts to make the zookeeper installation a bit more modular
(assuming that other folks will want to add other dlms as plugins),
and addresses the service start issues with zookeeper under
ubuntu/upstart.

Zookeeper is not going to be installed by default. Services need to
ask for it with use_dlm.

Change-Id: I33525e2b83a4497a57ec95f62880e0308c88b34f

commit_message:
Use choices kwarg when defining string options with defined choices

The ssh_connect_method and ssh_auth_method config options only allow
defined sets of choices, so enforce that using the choices kwarg with
StrOpt.

Change-Id: I862e1d6add8d74085987f7b86b3b8a4e67afe937

commit_message:
Group changes by topic having specific prefix - 'spec/'

Add simple check that change topic is prefixed by 'spec/' and use it to
group changes as src+spec to single build. Value after prefix may be any,
but it's required to be unique for only two changes - one to OpenStack
project, and other to build spec project.

Change-Id: I7cb305d9d0b9d6715951763ce72efb06a7c878f1
Closes-Bug: #1514873

commit_message:
Fix freezer-db-init when no config file is found

The freezer-db-init script was exiting with error when the freezer-api
configuration file was not found.
This is now fixed and the script correctly uses default values.

Change-Id: I1789aa2c4bd72378b11db602fce68ded2d29e974

commit_message:
Only use GET_PIP_URL when it is set

The logic in scripts/scripts-library.sh was recently changed with
respect to installing pip, however the conditional wasn't updated to
only use GET_PIP_URL when it is set.  This simple commits flips the
if statement to use a '-n' (checking if GET_PIP_URL is non-empty
instead) of a '-z'.

Change-Id: I6ace12f183e944a6cee2d7ab722424152f5eb419

commit_message:
Add functional test cases for swarm baymodel/bay

This patch adds TestSwarmAPIs test class, aimed to test Docker API/and
swarm related api function, we create a bay while setupClass, and destroy
it after test cases finished. Even without any cased added, at least we can
ensure swarm bay can be created successfully.

This will help to ensure any HOT/yml change won't break swarm's cluster
basic functions.

I leave a todo, we need more works to test container actions.

Since we have created a bay, so we can add more case using magnum client to
test container actions, will do this by followed patch.

Depends-On: Ifa028f6f30b7c2bb7b1dd32b22669379e162c7c5
Partially implements: blueprint swarm-functional-testing
Change-Id: I5c3bc5d7735cce17a45887359d1fb44d12dbba48

(4 comments)

I am very much against this running by default. This modifies the host services (stopping apache and mysql) and we do not do that _anywhere_ else in Kolla by design.

If this check is the be enabled by default, then these should be asserts and not enables. We need to assert the service is running. That is what a "check" would do.

Additionally, this runs across all of the hosts and not a subset, so its not just checking services on the same host, its checking across all of the hosts.

I would prefer to see the "precheck" task assert anythign that needs to be asserted, but change nothing in the environment. Check that the configs don't conflict, check the docker daemon is running, check nothing is binding to the appropriate ports, etc.

This should also be a blueprint since it will require more work than whats presented here and I am -2 on this work as is.'}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2015-11-03 23:11:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
Add playbook for hosts pre-deployment checks (ports, files)

This playbook runs on hosts before deployment to be sure we don't
have any conflicting services running and systems are in expected
state.

DocImpact

Change-Id: If5f288b7fbdf269697ca834da4eb969b61683ca0
Partially-implements: blueprint precheck-tasks

commit_message:
Add "unreleased" release notes page

We need a release notes page to show notes for unreleased versions by
scanning the "current" branch. This ensures that notes files cannot be
merged if they break the releasenotes job.

Change-Id: Ic0614c37a67ebd28d1da0c0947c69c753833c870
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>
(cherry picked from commit eeb12b940ac3b7f68573a9ffa82cb3f76214a8cf)

commit_message:
scheduler: refactory pci consume_resource

The stats reporting should be a read-only summary view,
which means the code in PciDeviceStats that currently
handles claiming resources can be moved to manager layer.
this patch did the move.

blueprint resource-objects

Change-Id: Idb82d6a3da09120d83c4415ff208339400459102

commit_message:
Removed new=True argument from create_connection

It's deprecated in neutron. It was also unused since Juno.

Related-Bug: #1506492
Depends-On: I57b0229c2b6028796cd10bbbfc9b166cf8a6dab0
Change-Id: I2ebad27776176ddb1749ce3004580e105cfe3cea

Setting TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR in tox.ini is breaking the gate,

should be set manually.

commit_message:
Remove TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR in the api tox env

Setting TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR in tox.ini is breaking the gate,
probably because of a tox bug [1].
Removing the line to unblock the gate. This implies that
for local execution of the tests TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR
should be set manually.

[1] https://bitbucket.org/hpk42/tox/issues/285/tox-220-breaks-some-toxini-config-files

Change-Id: If3742b6eabe295a5aaeb4901c55909a70c451698
Closes-bug: #1515335
(cherry picked from commit a32e31a624cf5190ed267effed8f7db2c9919949)

commit_message:
Use a condition (and/or a dummy one) instead of a lock

Instead of having to spin in the wait method, just use
a condition and block until stopping has actually happened,
when stop happens, it will use the notify_all method to let
any blockers release.

Closes-Bug: #1505730

I don't think I like removing the parameter and making it a resource instead. We lose the ability to specify a certain password, and many organizations may have security rules about passwords, so we need to allow them to specify whatever password that may be.

(1 comment)

One thing inline.

I'm also inclined to agree with James about making this unsettable, although I do see that we did the same thing with mysql's root password so maybe we just need to have a more general discussion about that.  I particular I think we should set it to something longer than 10 characters if we're going to do this.  I'm reasonably certain a 10 char password isn't going to be enough for the truly paranoid. :-)

I don't think I would block the patch on that (this is a whole lot better than "guest"), but it's a discussion worth having at some point.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-03 18:04:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Sumit, it doesn't. Simply commit to running open elections for PTL in a manner consistent with the upstream OpenStack community projects and that's fine. :)

In fact, there's no reason you need to have a single PTL or even have a PTL. The requirements are that you must have open and transparent elections if you have a PTL, and that if you don't have a PTL, then your contributor community must have documented liaisons for cross-project stuff like release management, docs, etc.

-jay"}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-03-10 12:19:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-03-30 13:54:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

One of the points in the new project requirements is the following:

    * Where it makes sense, the project cooperates with existing projects
      rather than gratuitously competing or reinventing the wheel

I feel that the importance of this requirement varies depending on the layer of the stack we're talking about.  For a higher-level project supporting cloud-native applications, I'm less concerned about overlap.  For a very base component of compute IaaS (networking in this case), I'm *very* concerned about it.

As I understand it, part of what this project provides is a networking API that can translate to Neutron, but also provides native networking backends.  We've already had a messy history with Neutron and nova-network.  Our failure to set expectations and get back to a single network stack has been damaging to OpenStack, IMO.  I feel that adding another networking project causes further fragmentation at a layer where we should be avoiding it as much as we can.

If there seemed to be broad support for this project as the future of networking for OpenStack, my feelings would be different.  Since that does not seem to be the case (yet, at least), I think the OpenStack mission is better served by not including this project."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-03-30 14:12:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

(2 comments)

I don't see a direct response to Doug's question yet. I'm wondering why the patch author has chosen to ignore it?

To answer it, yes, this is a networking API. If we do spin nova-network out [1] and we approve this project, we'll have 3 networking projects in OpenStack. I'm not sure if getting a hat trick [2] in this particular case is something we want to be proud about.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-March/060029.html
[2] http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hat-trick"}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2015-03-30 15:28:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Hi Doug, Thanks for your comment, and my apologies that I did not notice and respond earlier. To answer your questions -

GBP manages policy that deals with Application intent (the desires of the developer), and Operational constraints (the demands of the operator). An example of application policy is “allow secure access to MyApp”; an operational constraint is “access to MyApp is subject to IDS”.

GBP is an application-focussed API that the aims to capture the user's intent for configuring the cloud infrastructure. It does not aim to be another networking API, and in fact requires Neutron and its networking API for its functioning."}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2015-03-30 16:06:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

(2 comments)

Hi Kyle, I have responded to Doug's comment and it was an oversight that I did not notice it earlier, so my apologies again. To reiterate, GBP is not a networking API; its an API that aims to capture the user’s intent for providing and consuming applications. It does not replace the existing Neutron networking API, and in fact requires Neutron. Similarly, GBP requires and leverages other OpenStack components, Nova, Keystone, Heat."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-30 16:13:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2015-03-30 16:24:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Hi Russell, Thanks for your review of the proposal. GBP is not a networking API, and it’s objective is not to provide an API that translates to Neutron. GBP is an API to capture the user’s intent for providing and consuming applications in the cloud context. GBP does not aim to replace any of the fundamental IaaS components that OpenStack has, and it either already interfaces, or aims to in the future, with all of those components. GBP requires Neutron, Nova, Cinder, Keystone, Heat (and other foundational components) to run; it cannot work without them. I have also responded to similar comments inline. Hope this clarifies.'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-03-30 16:44:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

(1 comment)

Sumit, can you confirm that GBP can run in a mode without neutron? I know at one point the goal was to obviate the need for Neutron, is that still the case?

Also, it's still not clear to me where the integration with other OpenStack components happens. It's obvious with Neutron, but I don't see anything happening with cinder or swift here, or nova for that matter.

Just trying to understand some things here as GBP has evolved over the past year."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-03-30 16:54:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

So, regarding the "is this a network API or not" bit, can you help me understand what these drivers are?  They look like native drivers that bypass Neutron from my brief look.  I'm having a hard time mapping what you say GBP does to what I find in the specs and code.

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/stackforge/group-based-policy/tree/gbpservice/neutron/services/grouppolicy/drivers'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-03-30 17:04:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

I found http://group-based-policy.readthedocs.org/en/latest/usage.html#how-does-gbp-work

Does a good job of explaining things'}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2015-03-30 17:11:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(1 comment)

Hi Kyle, GBP cannot run in a mode without Neutron. I am also not aware that there was a goal to obviate the need for Neutron, or any other OpenStack components. As regards integration with other OpenStack components, the integration with Nova is triggered today via the GBP UI components. This will be expanded such that a richer policy modeled can be supported that takes into consideration compute-specific aspects. Similar integration with the storage components is also planned. Its not in the code yet.'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-03-30 17:14:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(1 comment)

Sumit, the official docs [1] point to the ability to run without neutron, am I misunderstanding something here? Seems to me like that approach is supported by the code to from what I can tell.

http://group-based-policy.readthedocs.org/en/latest/usage.html#how-does-gbp-work'}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2015-03-30 17:25:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Hi Russell, What you refer to as “native” drivers, are drivers which talk to backends that expose their own policy model. The GBP model has Policy Target Groups (PTG) comprising of Policy Targets (PT), and policies are associated with these PTGs. The “native” drivers map the GBP policy language to backend policy language. This does not bypass Neutron. For connectivity between two PTs, Neutron ports have to be created for those PTs (which means Neutron networks and subnets also have to be created). This is achieved by interfacing with Neutron and the configured ML2 mechanism drivers.'}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2015-03-30 17:37:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Hi Kyle, GBP cannot run without Neutron in any configuration mode. The docs do not indicate this either. What the doc says is that one can either deploy a driver that maps the policy constructs to backends that have their own policy constructs, or there is a reference Neutron mapping available, which maps the network aspects of policy to Neutron constructs. Note that in each of the above cases, Neutron is required. Per my earlier response to Russell’s comment - for connectivity between two policy targets, Neutron ports have to be created for those PTs (which means Neutron networks and subnets also have to be created). This is achieved by interfacing with Neutron and the configured ML2 mechanism drivers.

It is true that currently the most mature aspect of this project is the mapping of the application policy constructs to rendering it for network connectivity. This is probably being misunderstood as the GBP API being a replacement for the prevailing networking API.'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-03-30 17:37:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Ok, so we've got both Neutron and GDB talking to the SDN controller.

I'm taking a closer look at the code to try to understand.  Like you said, i see that Neutron is still used for port creation.

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/stackforge/group-based-policy/tree/gbpservice/neutron/plugins/ml2/drivers/grouppolicy/apic/driver.py

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/stackforge/group-based-policy/tree/gbpservice/neutron/services/grouppolicy/drivers/cisco/apic/apic_mapping.py

However, it seems the rest of Neutron is not used / bypassed.  Can you comment on how this works with the rest of the Neutron API?"}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2015-03-30 17:44:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-03-30 17:47:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Sumit, so, is the plan that in the future this will somehow integrate with storage, compute, etc.? Because it appears to be networking only now. If that's the case, then this would look to overlap a bit with Congress.

Also, when using the native drivers, do you only use neutron to create and delete ports? You don't use any of the neutron routers, security groups, etc.  Seems like it's replicating existing neutron functionality here if this is the case. I think this would be confusing to openstack users, given the situation we're in with nova-network and neutron already. Throwing another thing in the mix seems like it would add more confusion."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-03-30 18:13:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

Sumit, I'm sorry to change my vote on this, but I just saw this in the GBP docs:

 "At this time, use of both the GBP and Neutron APIs as end user facing APIs in parallel is not supported."

My concerns from almost a year ago on the ML that GBP was essentially trying to replace Neutron do indeed seem to be on the mark. :(

I therefore agree with Russell that this particular project does indeed seem to trying to replace a core part of OpenStack as it exists today.

What I am wondering, however, is whether the Congress project could be said to be attempting pretty much the same thing: circumventing the OpenStack APIs (or rewriting them, essentially) in order to make intent-based APIs the new OpenStack API standard? 

-jay'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-03-30 18:19:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

"What I am wondering, however, is whether the Congress project could be said to be attempting pretty much the same thing: circumventing the OpenStack APIs (or rewriting them, essentially) in order to make intent-based APIs the new OpenStack API standard?"

That's definitely a valid concern.  My impressions of Congress were that the layering was much more clear and that it wasn't actually trying to be the interface for creation/management of any OpenStack resources.  It seemed to be purely about doing status checks against the current state of the infrastructure against defined policy.  We should dig into it on the Congress review, though, to be sure.'}, {'account_id': 7987, 'date': '2015-03-30 18:29:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Hi Russel, 

Since you picked code from a vendor driver I wrote, I'll try to answer you doubts.
The usage of Neutron is not limited to port creation. In fact, the whole "core" Neutron model is used (except for Security Groups, but that's only for the apic driver).
Given the inheritance from the Resource Mapping Driver, Subnets and networks are used for IPAM and multi-tenancy, the DHCP agent is also absolutely needed in order for everything to work properly (the agent is, as usual, configured by Neutron).
As a matter of fact, I'm experimenting with a new Neutron type driver and agent [1] that I plan pushing to Neutron once properly tested (or probably on the vendor driver tree, given the ongoing vendor split). One more item in the agenda (for the base mapping model) is to leverage the newest Pool allocation feature that will be available starting from Neutron K. 
 
Last but not least, the APIC ML2 driver referenced here [2] is not the only one that has to run in order for the apic driver to work! That one is a mere notification expedient (looking on using actual Neutron notifications for that). all the connectivity logic is handled by the reference Neutron ML2 OVS driver.
 
I hope this clears your doubts! I'll be available both here and on IRC to answer any further question, or to have a code walkthrough if you like :)!

[0] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/164920/
[1] https://github.com/noironetworks/python-opflex-agent/tree/master/opflexagent
[2] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/stackforge/group-based-policy/tree/gbpservice/neutron/plugins/ml2/drivers/grouppolicy/apic/driver.py'}, {'account_id': 2035, 'date': '2015-03-30 18:47:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

Some additional questions/concerns:

* I think the assertion that the group based policy project is 'a policy
  framework for cloud infrastructure' is, at best, a
  mischaracterization.  The history of the project and its current
  source tree indicate that it is primarily intended to provide a
  networking abstraction layer.  Why is this not being stated clearly?

* Group based policy is necessarily invasive when it comes to Neutron's
  API.  When enabled, it has to change the behavior of Neutron in
  order to enforce policy constraints.  What danger does this present
  to compatibility between clouds?

1: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Congress"}, {'account_id': 6316, 'date': '2015-03-30 21:09:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

We need to clarify and simplify networking for our users, I am not in support of anything that takes us in any networking direction other than that.'}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2015-03-30 21:28:28.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2015-03-30 21:31:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Setting this to "Work in Progress", as more time will be needed to respond to the comments, and update the documentation to clarify some aspects. Thanks all for your reviews and comments.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-30 21:33:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-governance-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/02/161902/10/check/gate-governance-docs/82ed9b4//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 40s'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-03-30 21:39:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 7987, 'date': '2015-03-30 23:04:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Hi Maru, to your previous comment:

* The high level networking abstraction is definitively one part of the project. In fact, it's the only implemented abstraction we have at this early stage (and that's for historical reasons, as you correctly mentioned). However, the mission of GBP is to provide an intent high level abstraction for eventually describing multiple kind of policies (Compute, Storage, Networking) -without- replacing -any- of the existing Openstack projects. Do you think we should add a note in the mission statement saying that our current implementation only covers networking? I hope it doesn't seem too confusing.

* I'm not sure what you mean by *changing the behavior of Neutron in order to enforce policy constraints*. Can you please clarify that?"}, {'account_id': 2035, 'date': '2015-03-30 23:33:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Ivan:

Thank you for answering my first question.  So, why exactly is it necessary that this project to exist vs cooperating/collaborating with Congress, which appears to have a largely similar mission?

As to your question, I was under the impression that group based policy would be installable alongside neutron and that the behavior of the Neutron API would potentially differ in behavior due to policy enforcement.  The fact that the group based policy API cannot be used alongside Neutron's API, as per Jay's comment, suggest this point is moot, and in its current form a cloud using group based policy would not be able to provide any guarantee of networking api compatibility with a cloud using Neutron."}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2015-03-31 02:14:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Hi Jay, Russell, Kyle, As mentioned earlier, the objective of GBP has been to complement the APIs of the existing OpenStack components. However, your opinions expressed here indicate that this comes across replacing existing APIs. We need more time and discussions to reconcile this disconnect. We are hoping that we can get your guidance on how to do this and make constructive progress. In the meanwhile, I have set this proposal to WIP.

Jay, specifically regarding the sentence that you pointed out in the documentation, I think it is not conveying the desired meaning. One can use the Neutron API and the GBP API in the same deployment. When using the Neutron API, all Neutron resources are rendered exactly they would be without GBP. When using the GBP API, both the policy and the Neutron resources are rendered, and one can still access the Neutron resources just the same way as with Neutron alone.'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-03-31 12:54:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: -Code-Review

setting back to 0 since it's marked as WIP for now."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-03-31 15:32:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Sumit, my advice to you is to be honest here: This is a project to implement a new networking API. It's nothing more at this time. I looked at the tutorials submitted for Vancouver [1] and the ODL Summit [2] and I don't see anything in there regarding storage or CPU. The mere fact this project exists in OpenDaylight and not in any storage related project is further proof of it's network centricity. Additionally, looking at the code, it's obvious this is just a networking API. Even worse, it's a networking API which you expect to expose to users! Given the fact we're in the middle of trying to unwind the nova-network to neutron situation we find ourselves in [3], I find it a bit disingenuous you are proposing a 3rd networking API at this time.

[1] https://openstacksummitmay2015vancouver.sched.org/event/fe712eb5f27186ffd64ed787244af4f3#.VRq4e0b__4k
[2] http://events.linuxfoundation.org/events/opendaylight-summit/program/schedule
[3] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-March/060029.html"}, {'account_id': 7987, 'date': '2015-03-31 16:51:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Maru:

This project will certainly collaborate with Congress! The main difference (but I hope the Congress folks chime in for further explanation) is that GBP is a domain specific policy language (since it works specifically with Openstack) while Congress is domain agnostic. One more difference is that Congress is used for governance, while GBP is intended for policy enforcement.

On your second point, GBP uses Neutron "as is" without changing its behavior/API at all! 
I think there's a misunderstanding on the fact that GBP doesn't support working "alongside" with Neutron. What that means is that the user could go to Neutron and change the topology, but GBP *may* not be able to catch and report all the changes! Think of it as an user adding an extra flow rule to an OVS controlled by a Neutron agent... IIRC correctly that's not supported in Neutron today, in the sense that Neutron can't guarantee that the change won't break the data path unless you know what you are doing. That was probably not the best example, but I hope the point went through.

Even when GBP is around, you can absolutely implement your use cases through Neutron. You could even have entire topologies working through Neutron that GBP don't know about and nothing would go wrong! I hope it's a little bit clearer now.

Kyle:

Since I've submitted the talk referred in you latest comment, I'll try to answer your concern. The fact that *today* the only intent API abstraction implemented is network-centric is obviously true and not hidden anywhere (the code is pretty eloquent).
But does it have anything to do with the project mission? Even our networking abstraction will certainly evolve, and new ones will be born and grow with the help of the community as it has been so far, do you think we should add a note in the mission statement to point out that, at this early stage, only a network abstraction exists?

As far as the hands-on lab is concerned the main objective is to show how the intent abstraction works. My hope is that showing this for networking will make it easy to understand the further evolution of the project.
I hope this helped a bit, thanks a lot for your comments and feel free to contact me for any further question.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-31 21:15:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-04-03 10:00:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

While both are higher-level, intent-driven APIs, I think this is different from Congress.

The way I understand it, Congress defines external rules and measures / audits compliance to those rules -- it's closer to Ceilometer than to Neutron. It's also extremely agnostic of what is getting audited, and does not require vendor drivers to do its job.

My main gripe with GBP (beyond the Neutron dilution aspect) is that it's not just a high-level API built on top of classic iaas REST low-level APIs. It interfaces with hardware and therefore requires its own drivers. The hardware it interfaces with is likely to already have OpenStack drivers to talk to the corresponding IaaS component. I think asking vendors to develop drivers for two OpenStack components for the same hardware is a bit unreasonable.

It's not a pure replacement for Neutron either -- it actually still needs Neutron to work. So we can't give it a free pass in the name of healthy competition and the potential for it to become one day neutron-ng. (FTR I wouldn't support that option either, since I think a IaaS platform needs a IaaS REST low-level networking API).

We wouldn't be having this discussion if GBP high-level API just proxied to other OpenStack low-level APIs. If this was just about translating "firewall everything but HTTPS" into a set of Neutron calls, then I would be +1 on it. It's the mixed bag of competition and cooperation which makes this hard to accept.'}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2015-04-03 21:10:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

I'm responding to the following from Thierry: "My main gripe with GBP (beyond the Neutron dilution aspect) is that it's not just a high-level API built on top of classic iaas REST low-level APIs. It interfaces with hardware and therefore requires its own drivers. The hardware it interfaces with is likely to already have OpenStack drivers to talk to the corresponding IaaS component. I think asking vendors to develop drivers for two OpenStack components for the same hardware is a bit unreasonable."

I'd like to clarify that GBP does not require any special back-end-specific policy drivers. The resource_mapping policy driver does everything needed using only neutron's existing low-level APIs. This works fine with any neutron configuration, using any neutron back-end, as long as the required standard neutron resources are available.

The ability to configure GBP to use an alternative policy driver that maps GBP constructs to neutron resources differently than the resource_mapping driver, and/or has some direct interaction with the back-end, is purely an optimization. This flexibility in GBP is key to enabling OpenStack deployments to take advantage of the scalability, performance, and security offered by intent-based features in networking controllers, such as in ODL and various vendors' products. But no neutron back-end vendor is required to provide their own policy driver to work with GBP, unless they want to implement such optimizations.

Also, I'd expect this optimized vendor-specific GBP driver code to eventually move out-of-tree, following the lead of neutron's plugin/driver decomposition effort, so GBP reviewers will need not be concerned with these vendor-specific optimizations.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-08-21 12:31:07.000000000', 'content': 'Topic changed from gbp-project to formal-vote'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-10-06 19:28:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Workflow-1

Setting Workflow-1 until the proposer unWIPs it'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-11-13 13:37:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: -Workflow'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-11-13 13:37:23.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

At the November 10, 2015 Technical Committee meeting, the TC members made the decision that applications that are considered work-in-progress by their proposers should be abandoned and re-proposed when ready to be reconsidered (rather than be workflow-1).

If (and when) you feel your project team has made significant progress in those areas, feel free to restore this change (by clicking on the "Restore change" button), remove [WIP] from the commit message and rebase the application on top of the current status of the governance repository.

Feel free to reach out to TC members if you have any question.'}]

[{'created': '2015-03-05 21:22:55.000000000', 'message': 'Add Group Based Policy Project

Group Based Policy (GBP) [1] is a policy framework consisting of declarative,
intent-based abstractions for cloud infrastructure coupled with an enforcement
engine designed to enable scalable automation.

GBP is currently an Open Source stackforge project. It was originally
conceived and presented during the OpenStack Icehouse Design Summit, Hong Kong,
in Nov 2013 [2]. It has evolved through discussions that happened in the
subsequent design summits [3][4], in weekly IRC meetings since Dec 2013 [5],
mailing list discussions in openstack-dev, in #openstack-gbp, and coding
sprints [6].

The GBP core team has ten reviewers [7] who were chosen based on their design
and code contributions to the project. The project follows standard OpenStack
practices with designs being discussed in gerrit specs [8], public code reviews
[9], bugs tracked in Launchpad, a test-driven gate, and stable branches.

GBP leverages other OpenStack services such as Keystone, Neutron,
Nova, Heat, Horizon, and aims to integrate with other services to
comprehensively manage and automate policy enforcement across infrastructure
components.

GBP has an extensible architecture that allows for plugging in open source and
vendor policy drivers. It integrates with the OpenDaylight Network Controller,
and three other vendor backends, with others being planned. GBP has its own
client package, and also UI and automation packages, that plug into Horizon and
Heat respectively. GBP Juno release is available with packages for Fedora, Red
Hat, Ubuntu, and also devstack-based install for developers [10].

commit_message:
WIP - Add Group Based Policy Project

Group Based Policy (GBP) [1] is a policy framework for cloud infrastructure.
It is based on declarative, intent-based abstractions that build on existing
OpenStack interfaces to enable scalable automation.

GBP is currently an Open Source stackforge project. It was originally
conceived and presented during the OpenStack Icehouse Design Summit, Hong Kong,
in Nov 2013 [2]. It has evolved through discussions that happened in the
subsequent design summits [3][4], in weekly IRC meetings since Dec 2013 [5],
mailing list discussions in openstack-dev, in #openstack-gbp, and coding
sprints [6].

GBP has an elected PTL [7] and a core team of ten reviewers [8] who were chosen
based on their design and code contributions to the project. The project follows
standard OpenStack practices with designs being discussed in gerrit specs [8],
public code reviews [10], bugs tracked in Launchpad, a test-driven gate, and
stable branches. The project has a diverse set of contributors spanning
many organizations [11].

GBP leverages other OpenStack services such as Keystone, Neutron,
Nova, Heat, Horizon, and aims to integrate with other services to
comprehensively manage and automate policy enforcement across infrastructure
components. The project has designated liaisons [12] to help collaborate with
other project teams and keep GBP in sync with the rest of the ecosystem.

GBP has an extensible architecture that allows for plugging in open source and
vendor policy drivers. It integrates with the OpenDaylight Network Controller,
and three other vendor backends, with others being planned. GBP has its own
client package, and also UI and automation packages, that plug into Horizon and
Heat respectively. GBP Juno release is available with packages for Fedora, Red
Hat, Ubuntu, and also devstack-based install for developers [13].

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GroupBasedPolicy
[2] http://icehousedesignsummit.sched.org/event/e914b45ccce0b6f70b8b6fce6b0f19af
[3] http://junodesignsummit.sched.org/event/e9dd467daf0cae0cdb29ee97d64bbf56#.VPI17rPF-Q0
[4] http://kilodesignsummit.sched.org/event/98dc4255384e340682137c8a7ee7e60d#.VPI2d7PF-Q0

[6] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GroupBasedPolicy/JunoCodeSprint
[7] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-March/059317.html
[8] https://review.openstack.org/#/admin/groups/438,members
[9] https://github.com/stackforge/group-based-policy-specs
[10] https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+project:stackforge/group-based-policy+branch:master,n,z

(1 comment)

The name concerns me a bit, since we have "openstack kilo" as a release name, but maybe I'm over-thinking. The -1 is for the URL, see my comment inline.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-12 11:57:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-08-12 12:19:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote-1

Code here has been posted 5 days ago, it's a bit early to be able to assess if the project team is "one of us" and behaves like an OpenStack project. If I were to answer right now my answer would probably be "not yet" (no IRC meeting, no thread on the ML, self-approved code reviews...)

The new StackForge governance means that there is now no cost in starting up the project there and migrating it to an OpenStack project later. My recomendation would be to finish setting up the project there and apply once the team is fully formed.'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2015-08-16 01:02:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote-1 Code-Review-1

This is a reimplementation of the Monasca API with no mention of why this project wants to exist separate from the Monasca project. It also currently has one contributor, unless you count a patch to the README file. While it's possible that there might be value in OpenStack bringing this into the fold, I think it's quite premature to do so right now. I _highly_ recommend working with the existing Monasca team and community if there are features you want that they don't have, or use cases that are not being addressed - or if that's not possible and a competing project is actually desired, I would like to see a well thought out justification for why that will be beneficial."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-08-17 18:46:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Rollcall-Vote-1'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2015-08-18 09:15:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1 Rollcall-Vote-1

I agree with the previous comments. However, I'm also curious to know:

@Tong Li:

- What led you to request inclusion to the Big Tent on such an early stage of the project?
- Were you aware of the policies/workflows - other than the big tent - before submitting the patch?
- Is there any guidance/support we (or the rest of the community) can provide?

For instance, I'd recommend you to start by contacting folks from the Monasca team. I believe Monty's comments are very relevant and the points he's made will impact this and any future attempt to join OpenStack"}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-08-19 09:46:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

This was discussed at the TC meeting yesterday. The outcome of the discussion is that:

- the Kiloeyes project team should operate as an unofficial ("Stackforge") project for a while before it applies to become an official OpenStack project team. Ideally the project would operate for a few months and produce some sort of release so its processes and output can be evaluated.

- the Kiloeyes project team should publicly reach out to  the Monasca project team and see if there are avenues for collaboration (and/or merging the two efforts).

We suggest you abandon this change and re-propose when the above conditions are met.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-08-21 12:33:19.000000000', 'content': 'Topic set to formal-vote'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-10-02 12:10:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1 Rollcall-Vote-1

agree this is too early'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-11-13 13:35:22.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

At the November 10, 2015 Technical Committee meeting, the TC members made the decision that deferred applications should be abandoned and re-proposed when ready to be reconsidered. 

The Kiloeyes application was deferred last time it was proposed because the project team needed to start working before we could assess that it's really behaving like the rest of the OpenStack community. You can already create repositories under the openstack/* namespace. It was also requested that the Kiloeyes team reaches out to the Monasca team to explore avenues for collaboration (and/or merging the two efforts).

If (and when) you feel your project team has made significant progress in those areas, feel free to restore this change (by clicking on the "Restore change" button) and rebase the application on top of the current status of the governance repository.

Feel free to reach out to TC members if you have any question.'}]
