This needs a formal TC vote, so adding the corresponding topic keyword.'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2015-09-16 17:49:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

According to the GH[0] repo, there are currently 2 commits, 1 contributor and no useful code.

Is it Ok to bring in empty projects just based on their mission?

AFAICT, there's nothing that prevents doing this but I feel it's a bit weird to bring in projects that are still not usable at all.

-1 for now, I just want to make sure there's some agreement on this.



[0] https://github.com/openstack/kosmos"}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2015-09-16 21:08:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Flavio, I don't know if there's a policy. I recall that coming up in TC meetings a few times, with the answer always being, "in the tent, if they're 'one of us', why wait?". Since this project is made up of cores from existing tent projects, that seemed to fit.

Since your question has come up multiple times, maybe the answer/guidelines need to be written down somewhere?

Let us know what the policy is, and we'll proceed. Thanks.'}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2015-09-17 14:06:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1

I think Flavio's question is a good one, but I'm also good with Doug's response. I have no concerns about this set of humans being inside of the set of us humans."}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2015-09-18 07:08:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I'm more than happy to trust this set of humans, especially because this set of humans is familiar with OpenStack, the big tent and the workflows.

My concern still remains though, because there have been proposed projects that were not compliant. This made me worry about completely new projects going in the wrong direction (nothing that couldn't be fixed in the future).

We should probably have this written down somewhere to avoid deciding in a case by case basis.

Keeping the -1 for now to, hopefully, help others notice this concern but, as I mentioned above, I'd be more than happy to +1 this proposal if we are ok with adding empty projects in general."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-09-18 12:53:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I'm fine with approving a project at its very beginning, but I like to consider it case-by-case (like any other project application).  It depends if there's anything in the proposal that worries me about going in a bad direction.  In this case, here are some points that led to my +1:

- I think the idea makes good sense.  It's something not addressed today, and the proposal is to implement with integration with existing services where it makes sense.

- It's people already deeply involved with other OpenStack projects, so I'm confident they understand what it means to run an OpenStack project."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-09-22 09:54:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

FWIW we did approve empty project teams in the past (packaging-deb for example) based on their mission and team members.

That said, I share Flavio's concern. I'm generally more comfortable with incubating teams outside of governance so that they can iterate fast and have something to show before we apply that layer of bureaucracy/recognition on them. Now that we removed the painful stackforge rename step and can directly create openstack/* repositories, asking to be added to the tent very early on has little benefit.

If you *need* it, it sends the wrong signal ("we have an idea but no team yet, so we need to be 'official' to efficiently bootstrap the team").'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-09-22 15:12:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 10980, 'date': '2015-09-22 15:49:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Thierry, I wouldn't say we 'need' it. The project will continue similarly with or without. We are applying now because we meet the criteria I've seen so far, and I'm just dealing with paperwork that can take awhile as a matter of course.

That said, if you want to avoid submissions like this, the TC does need to provide better guidance as to when it's appropriate."}, {'account_id': 8099, 'date': '2015-09-22 18:23:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I would echo Doug's comment - we don't need it, but as we were in "bootstrap / admin mode" we wanted to get all of the project init work done early.

I don't see a huge amount of overhead involved over what we would have been doing in anyway - with the release:independant tag we are not tied to the traditional cycle yet and can iterate quickly.

My recollection, from both the the big tent and the stackforge retirement resolutions was that projects were just being judged on:

1. Willingness to be governed by the TC (we are)
2. Work towards the goals of OpenStack (we are)
3. Further the mission of OpenStack (I would like to think we would)

Being in the big tent is useful for other things as well - being able to say we are the OpenStack Global Load Balancing Project, being able to use the oslosphinx theme and, being able to publish to specs. and docs.openstack.org.

If there is something we missed, and we should come back in a cycle or so, so be it, but I would like us to be part of OpenStack officially, and not have to worry about it again in the future :)'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-09-22 19:22:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Rollcall-Vote+1

I'm OK with adding a budding project from proven community members."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-09-22 20:20:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2015-09-22 20:43:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Rollcall-Vote+1 Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2015-09-22 20:44:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-09-22 20:44:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-09-22 20:46:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1 Rollcall-Vote-1

I think we should wait as we have for others'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2015-09-22 20:48:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1 Rollcall-Vote-1

I'm not feeling curmudgeonly but I do think we have asked others to prove their work before joining. Let's give some time to see results."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-09-22 20:50:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Code-Review -Rollcall-Vote'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-09-25 10:00:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Since there is no consensus, we'll discuss it at the next meeting again before enforcing strict voting rules."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-09-28 21:33:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Code-Review -Rollcall-Vote

With the project bar so low, I'd really rather see clear consensus on this.  If there are concerns (there seem to be), then I'd rather abstain.

I'm actually fine going either way on this, really.  I think a "not yet" response here needs to go along with a new project guidelines patch that says something to the effect of "we really prefer new projects having operated for some time (a few months or some rough time guideline) before applying.  That gives us a better opportunity to ensure the project operates how we expect."'}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2015-09-28 21:43:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I really think the project idea is a good and supported by a good group of contributors.  I think we need a defined standard here about what kind of record we require to ensure that a project operates within our community standard.  So I'm a 'not yet' and we as the TC need better guidance on when to submit (i.e. what is the basic level of maturity required)."}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-09-29 18:03:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Rollcall-Vote'}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2015-09-29 20:09:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-09-29 20:19:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1 Rollcall-Vote-1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-29 20:47:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-09-30 01:39:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1 Rollcall-Vote-1

Sorry to be late to the vote party. I am on the side of waiting a bit to see what the project is all about before listing it as an official OpenStack project in the projects.yaml file.

Best,

-jay'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-09-30 09:14:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

FTR decision on this was delayed until after the repositories are set up and work has started on them. This shall forever be known as "the Kosmos jurisprudence".'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-09-30 14:38:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I posted a patch adding "the Kosmos jurisprudence" to the new project requirements here:

https://review.openstack.org/229456'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-11-13 13:33:21.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

At the November 10, 2015 Technical Committee meeting, the TC members made the decision that deferred applications should be abandoned and re-proposed when ready to be reconsidered. 

The Kosmos application was deferred last time it was proposed because the project team needed to start working before we could assess that it's really behaving like the rest of the OpenStack community. You can already create repositories under the openstack/* namespace.

If (and when) you feel your project team has made significant progress in those areas, feel free to restore this change (by clicking on the "Restore change" button) and rebase the application on top of the current status of the governance repository.

Feel free to reach out to TC members if you have any question.'}]

commit_message:
Add new project Kosmos

Kosmos is a new project, formed initially from members of Designate
and Neutron Lbaas, to provide global server load-balancing for
openstack clouds.

This is separate from both LBaaS and Designate, but heavily leverages
both.

Our long term aim is to create a global service (like Designate /
Keystone) that allows cloud users to balance their traffic across
multiple regions, or multiple cloud providers.

Both Neutron LBaaS and Designate will be first class citizens - the
default install for Kosmos will use both, but we are adopting a plugin
architecture that allows for different integrations, while maintaining
a consistent API.

A standard setup may look like this:

Customer Applications running behind Neutron LB in multiple regions.

Kosmos will constantly monitor these endpoints, and the LBaaS Status
API, and update DNS records in Designate to move traffic between the
endpoints.

Change-Id: I5ed4e8cea5e467cd04a4a44aa9f9c941a1b1b37d

The compass project seems to focus on sending their users outside the OpenStack community for discussion - http://www.syscompass.org/getinvolved.html - using google groups and external lists instead of normal community mechanisms like ask.openstack.org and the user list. 

I feel like we really want this to be part of the community, that means all in on our community mechanisms.'}, {'account_id': 9853, 'date': '2015-07-06 14:42:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Sean, thanks for the review! We forgot to update that portion of the project page. I have now updated it with openstack-dev mailing-list as the discussion forum for Compass. see http://www.syscompass.org/getinvolved.html'}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-07-06 19:12:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1 Rollcall-Vote-1

It seems to me that Compass is trying to be too many things in a single product/project: a little Triple-O, a little Tuskar, a little bit of os-ansible-deployment, a little of the OpenStack Chef cookbooks, a lot of Fuel, a part of Ironic (inspector), along with things like a monitoring and provisioning toolchain like Cobbler. In addition to that, it's not exclusively focused on OpenStack -- rather, it's a generic "distributed software-defined infrastructure installer". 

Because of the not-entirely-OpenStack part of Compass, I'm -1 on adding this to the openstack/ code namespace. I think it's perfectly fine to keep this on GitHub/stackforge.

-jay'}, {'account_id': 9853, 'date': '2015-07-06 20:31:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Jay, thanks for the comments.  One thing though is that Compass does not try to be everything. For example, for OS installation it  tries to enable and reuse Cobbler, or Ironic (in stand-alone mode). We are not trying to replace Ansible or Chef, but rather we create plugins that use them. Compass provides a unified API and user interface for different underlying configuration management technologies. 

You are correct that Compass is like Fuel, which represents a different approach of installation OpenStack than TripleO's. While we emphasize the extensibility of Compass to be able to support other systems, the project has been focused on OpenStack from the beginning and will continue to do so. We expect OpenStack to be the infrastructure in OpenStack's ecosystems and related projects. For example, Ceph is often used along with OpenStack, and OPNFV has ODL and OpenStack. Both Fuel, and TripleO(from RedHat) are active in OPNFV projects. We believe Compass provides values to OpenStack community by providing a single framework to deploy OpenStack and its ecosystem partners."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-07-07 20:29:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I agree with Jay's concerns here, and I'll use this project review to highlight the fact that when Jim's patch to deprecate stackforge merges [1], the TC will have to make the hard call on projects such as this to basically bit-bucket them. Is the TC ready for that kind of decision, or does retaining StackForge make sense?

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/192016/"}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-07-07 20:31:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I don't think it's bit-bucketing anything.  Saying "please get your hosting on on alternative platform" is different from throwing things away.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-07-07 20:44:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I'd be happy to see compass in openstack/ but I think it needs to be much closer process-and-community wise to OpenStack projects than it is today. Specifically I'm concerned about the open development and open community aspects."}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2015-07-10 12:46:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I think it checks most of the boxes for "Are you OpenStack" but it's also trying to be other things to other projects like NPV. So it seems a bigger umbrella than ours may serve you well.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-14 20:41:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-08-21 12:31:15.000000000', 'content': 'Topic changed from bp/s to formal-vote'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-11-13 13:28:51.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

At the November 10, 2015 Technical Committee meeting, the TC members made the decision that deferred applications should be abandoned and re-proposed when ready to be reconsidered. 

The Compass application was deferred last time it was proposed because the project needed to more fully adopt our open development and open community principles, and also reflect back on its scope (which seems to go well beyond OpenStack and therefore might be artificially limited by being developed as an OpenStack project).

If (and when) you feel your project team has made significant progress in those areas, feel free to restore this change (by clicking on the "Restore change" button) and rebase the application on top of the current status of the governance repository.

Feel free to reach out to TC members if you have any question.'}]

commit_message:
Add Compass to OpenStack Projects

The mission of Compass is to provide an extensible deployment and management framework
for OpenStack, and other distributed systems. It is currently an active project under
 stackforge. It currently supports OpenStack, Ceph, and OPNFV. Compass allows pluggible
underlying configuration management such as Ansible, Chef, etc. It also provides metadata
support, REST API and metadata-driven web UI. This allows a uniform API and Web-UI for
different flavors of OpenStack and its eco-system components, such as ODL, ONOS etc.

Adoption of Compass will help the community in ease-of-use of OpenStack, and will
empower eco-system buildup.

Compass project conforms to our community's four opens as specified in
http://governance.openstack.org/reference/new-projects-requirements.html

  1) Open Source: Apache v2.0 License.

  2) Open Development: we have been using stackforge and OpenStack tool chains since
  the start of the project. This includes gerrit code review, test-driven gates from
  community and our own CI, etc. The PTL acts as the liaison for cross-project teams,
  which includes collaborations within Openstack(Ironic, TripleO), and eco-systems such
  as OPNFV.

  3) Open Design. We presented at earlier design summits, and will continue to do so in
  the future. Blueprints on launchpad. We will also use IRC and openstack-dev ML to
  discuss design.

  4) Open Community. We have scheduled and will conduct weekly IRC meeting. We are also
  open to OPNFV community, and currently in active joint development of Intel's upcoming
  RSA(Rack Scale Architecture).

Related links:
  - wiki page: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Compass
  - project site: http://www.syscompass.org/
  - project in OPNFV: https://wiki.opnfv.org/compass4nfv

Change-Id: I6aacbf1e5bc295757d20d44ce6f4c8db23da1bfc

Not that it strictly matters, since zuul is not a project that follows g-r - but zuul uses GitPython==1.0.1 and gitdb==0.6.4 currently. I also know that various people package zuul for distros, so adding these two to openstack's requirements should not be particularly additional effort on distro's part.

Finally, while zuul currently lists >=0.3.3, I don't think adding a new requirement to g-r at an 0x version makes sense when at the time of our adding it there is a 1.x version available. So this looks fine to me."}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2015-11-05 06:15:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Add kolla to requirements family

Kolla would like to conform to the global requirements process
to be easy tested and integrated. To be able to do that,
gitdb and GitPython is needed to add in global requirements.
gitdb:
 it is actively maintained at:
     https://github.com/gitpython-developers/gitdb
 lioense:
   New BSD License
GitPython:
 it is actively maintained at:
      https://github.com/gitpython-developers/GitPython
 license:
    New BSD License.
We also not have any other libraries in our global requirements
which provide such functionality.
Change-Id: Id1044b44b21737e57122e892b0330d98623b6108

commit_message:
[zmq][matchmaker] Distinguish targets by listener types

In order to have a possibility to pass messages via different
pipelines (not over DEALER/ROUTER only) we need an information
in the name service about socket type assigned to the target.

Change-Id: I7cdba6c2c91af7f63ecca30c94faecef2c2eff8b
Closes-Bug: #1497326

commit_message:
Enable Protractor end-to-end testing.

This enables end-to-end testing with Protractor, along with some
basic route and page load testing for the home and project pages.
PhantomJS is used to execute tests, and API requests are mocked
using `protractor-http-mock` (see `test/e2e/mocks/`).

A new gulp `e2e` task is also added to prepare and execute the
tests, along with a shortcut, `npm run protractor`. The default
`npm run test` is also amended to include E2E tests, with unit
tests moved to the new shortcut `npm run unit`.

Change-Id: Idb2eef2d851035c715e23553db56fc80deeab8e7

commit_message:
[zmq] Make bind address configurable

Makes use of exisiting 'rpc_zmq_bind_address' option in
order to make binding address configurable.

Change-Id: Ia46fa03e54b0e92d3504d9a0ebd65171a283e073
Closes-Bug: #1515267

When trying to find a particular release request, it's more useful to

Change-Id: Ia42b76b7e27f0d24f50cacde15afb3087a2e75ec

commit_message:
include some details about how we want commit messages structured

When trying to find a particular release request, it's more useful to
have the name of the thing and the version than a description like "fix
bug XYZ".

Change-Id: Ia42b76b7e27f0d24f50cacde15afb3087a2e75ec

commit_message:
[zmq] Update zmq-deployment guide according to the new driver

New driver introduced some new options and changed its architecture.
The first update of the deployment guide after the driver being
reimplemented. Following driver updates should be reflected in the
guide as well.

Change-Id: Id8629907560e335dfcff688082fe943b3657568c
Closes-Bug: #1497278

@Bob, sorry, I see it here:

http://dd6b71949550285df7dc-dda4e480e005aaa13ec303551d2d8155.r49.cf1.rackcdn.com/62/237762/9/15586/logs/nova.conf

I didn't think about the xen CI since this isn't a xen-specific change, and the option was deprecated for a release, but yeah we missed it, sorry.

There have been some failures with the xen CI that are random (xen project ci anyway, some race bug in the libvirt code).  So I tend to miss the 3rd party CIs unless they are on changes that really hit them (like xen patches  in nova, hyper-v or vmware changes, etc).

This is a global change so we should have noticed.

Ultimately I wish we had a thing like elastic-recheck running on 3rd party CI so we could know when we have uncategorized bugs with those, but I don't think anyone is working on anything like that for all 3rd party CI people."}]

commit_message:
force_config_drive: StrOpt -> BoolOpt

The 'force_config_drive' option provides a way to force injection of
configuration drives on instances. Previously, this option supported
three values: 'always', 'True' and 'False'. However, the 'always'
value was deprecated in Liberty and can now be removed.

Remove this value and replace the existing 'StrOpt' with a 'BoolOpt'.
This also requires changing some unit tests to reflect the new value
for this parameter.

UpgradeImpact: This change removes support for the 'always' option.
    Configuration files providing this value will need to be updated
    accordingly.
DocImpact: This option is now a BoolOpt and documentation will need to
    be updated accordingly.
Change-Id: I0b4030ec1336fb1f2e721570c99a27a979e2847c

commit_message:
Avoid requesting get-pip.py multiple times

This patch prevents the contents of get-pip.py from being printed to the
console and it avoids retrieving the script more than once via curl unless
absolutely necessary.

Closes-bug: 1514988

Change-Id: I6b312dfac23c8b32dba71edcfc65f65858349893
(cherry picked from commit 2690d81c23e9c68be6be302fb0b86854e1a16ddd)

directories.

commit_message:
Move independent project releases

Remove from Liberty release page all deliverables that actually
don't have a stable/liberty branch (since they, in effect, don't
have a "liberty" release at all). Store those in a specific
releases directory.

Change-Id: I63cc10163dcc50c67ff23bd807b1a91394de7dc2

will make the code more diffiicult to read and maintain. Using jinja
templates will shorten the code and avoid dealing with complicated code.

the implementation of RST output.

commit_message:
diff_branches: use jinja templates to create the files

Generating docbook using lxml works fine, but the switch to RST tables
will make the code more diffiicult to read and maintain. Using jinja
templates will shorten the code and avoid dealing with complicated code.

This patch implements the use of jinja for docbook tables, and will ease
the implementation of RST output.

Change-Id: Ia5a75ced773b7e6e8faa7f89cb7620d986c47718

commit_message:
Updated from global requirements

Stolen from Ic7516b79ed1eea1330f008ce83c8727fd974bdd3 and added a forced
oslo.config:

   NOTE(tonyb) Horizon itself doesn't need oslo.config but
   django-openstack-auth (doa) 1.1.9 (which meets the requirements
   below) contains an uncapped dependancy on oslo.config.  Force this
   *BEFORE* doa so that when doa is installed the requirement is already
   met and 2.x isn;t installed.

Change-Id: I5c8d0b97b52535b2c0c3501aa7b16ef497768731

commit_message:
Fix check for local IPs in DNS upstream

Value loading and checking for DNS upstream now
ensures that any host IP is excluded from DNS
upstream values.

New function list_host_ip_addresses returns IPv4
addresses for specified or all network interfaces.

Change-Id: I4b9ba582dfe498d89f0344b7dee1b1dff775ae9f
Closes-Bug: #1513844

commit_message:
Unhardcode default interface from eth0

Now the first detected physical interface will be
used as the default network interface. If for any
reason no physical interfaces are detected, fuelmenu
will exit with an error.

New common.network method get_physical_ifaces returns
a sorted list of interfaces that are physical

New common.network method is_physical returns true
if the string 'virtual' is not in its sysfs realpath.

Change-Id: I8d5f0fbcc1426a94b433d1a097fb51cc6915c154
Closes-Bug: #1512479

commit_message:
Don't use duplicate filter names for functional testing

They are not supported by Python 3.x configparser module (you get
DuplicateOptionError if duplicate names are present).

This makes tests relying on rootwrap daemon to get stuck, because the daemon
fails to spawn, while we wait for results from the process.

Change-Id: I1628bb87b235a6b4bac53afda37402e986520f39
Related-Bug: #1515118

metadata: Switch to OpenStack namespace and bump to Kilo

This patch fixes the puppet forge namespace, and bump min dependency to Kilo
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Puppet/releases.

Change-Id: I2640446d5dfd6bea6e43a52e016a813ef78a105f

metadata: Switch to OpenStack namespace and bump to Kilo

This patch fixes the puppet forge namespace, and bump min dependency to Kilo
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Puppet/releases.

Change-Id: I05c7b80c2aa1cfbef02839fe1862c191a71a658b
Signed-off-by: Gael Chamoulaud <gchamoul@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Make task parameter mandatory in get_supported_boot_devices

Deprecation period for not having task parameter in
get_supported_boot_devices is over, this change removes this
possibility and also adds now required parameter to UCS management
interface.

Change-Id: Id049f040865abf4c2dd50e8d91c227b67c9204b9

commit_message:
Move Japanese install guide (debian) to /ja/

All of English version of the install guides are published now.
There is no reason to keep Japanese install guide for Debian
in the draft index.

Change-Id: I88745563db0b919aa2fb2c093e986db70c54271e

commit_message:
Use PCS's maintenance mode while updating configuration

During upgrades and updates where configuration is edited service restarts
can be triggered.  If pacemaker isn't in maintenance mode it may attempt to
restart the service while it's being restarted.  This in turn results in
failed deployments and failed stack updates.

This change enables "maintenance-mode" for steps 1-3 where configuration
is still being landed and services may get restarted automatically.

Change-Id: Ibbb86d6ed8221c47acef9383848eb7230fe59b7c

commit_message:
Change to 'has_extension' for a test mock

The change I4810493918af6ecb5bdad8f295733f9c9f7de32e missed
to change a test mock of 'has_extension'.
Notes: Because the client_plugin is a mock object,
so the test won't failed.

Change-Id: I570bb5dbec126d0eeccf6e0ef77b32ea5aa31076

section of the End User Guide.

commit_message:
Revert "OVS agent reacts to events instead of polling"

This might be associated to manifestation of bug #1514935

This reverts commit 1992d52d63dc32c63faa5a3f482d5b8ebe925a77.

Closes-Bug: #1514935

commit_message:
[WIP] Add assert:follows-standard-deprecation to ironic

Ironic has followed a one-cycle deprecation period for some time now;
we are happy to add the three-month requirement per the process
described by the tag.

TODO is a grenade job required to meet these requirements? Need to check
on the status of our grenade job.

Change-Id: I9980c6152aa40fd04acd786335ba92ca789984fe

commit_message:
lb: simplify how port admin_state_up is implemented

Setting the tap device's link state instead of
moving it in or out of the bridge.

Change-Id: I263e05a04d40477e3571e4c148c00ee5582a8bc6
Co-Authored-By: Sean M. Collins <sean@coreitpro.com>
Co-Authored-By: Darragh O'Reilly <darragh.oreilly@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Andreas Scheuring <andreas.scheuring@de.ibm.com>
Closes-Bug: #1312016

commit_message:
check if 'ironic' network exist in devops

 In release settings all networks are present.
 Since 'ironic' is optional component and 'ironic' network is
 created in devops ONLY if IRONIC_ENABLED=True we need
 to check that 'ironic' network exist in devops before trying to update
 release network settings.

Change-Id: Ic5acb0d15c0012a824b2381abda96d6e8aa7cfb9

commit_message:
Correct m1.micro exists test to fail correctly

The test always returned 1 because of placement of
quotes, but now correctly returns as soon as nova
flavor-list properly returns data, speeding up
the test and providing more accurate information.

Change-Id: If73342ceced5408e02d7a2ca49d8deead6e76845
Closes-Bug: #1511695

commit_message:
Revert "Add Pillow to test-requirements.txt"

This reverts commit 29478cbd7a8f3c848cd0c6f858798b18f7ec2ac4.

29478cbd7a8f3c848cd0c6f858798b18f7ec2ac4 was a quick fix to work around
missing libraries needed by Pillow 3.0.0.

This librarries have been added to devstack and thick slaves so this
hack is no longer needed in ironic.

Change-Id: I0e79d9865dfd8fce61a79fa6dc0d6d171e01709a
Depends-On: I881ad72e48a4da0a828706fcbbc51de7741db6c1

commit_message:
Fix oslo namespace in default log level

Default log level setup is broken for oslo.messaging since old oslo
namespace is used, oslo_messaging namespace should be used instead.

Also replace deprecated WARN log level with new WARNING for default
log level set.

Change-Id: Idd6ace4176fe6fd1148f1b4fcc1fa29dc966b61e
Closes-Bug: #1515908

commit_message:
Set _get_wt_snapshot fail_if_not_found default value

Most of the methods calling _get_wt_snapshot assume that this
argument defaults to True and do not pass it, causing a lot of
TypeErrors.

This patch adds the missing default value.

Change-Id: I5d7b26e490df7e49c8350779acbaa7b2c82a67ad

commit_message:
Update help message of test-runner to same format

Previously, the help message of --os-auth-url, "Authentication URL
(Env: OS_AUTH_URL)", is not same as other arguments of OS
environment variable. So update it to same format.

Change-Id: Iaed9b56016af8ce4c3470c55157458563b41ddcb
Closes-Bug: #1515781

Allow change owners to abandon in governance

abandon it, but more importantly, also restore it.

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
fix fuzzy search for same-distance case

get_fuzzy_matches() cannot handle case where all
commands have the same Levenshtein distance
from searched command. It will bomb-out with
IndexError (dist[i][1] referencing one element
after the end).

It also does not handle no-commands case or
the case where searched command is the prefix of
all commands. The latter two cases are minor, since
'help' and 'complete' commands are always present.

We fix it by iterating over the partial result
safely, consuming only candidates with distance==0
(prefix commands) and those of the same minimum
distance.

Closes-Bug: #1500445
Change-Id: Iae5e77b64dc0d96e040acdcadf019db66a416648

commit_message:
(WIP) Unhardcode predefined networks for neutron

    Neutron resources net04, net04_ext, and router04
    are now defined in hiera in neutron_config with
    the following keys, respectively:
      default_private_net
      default_floating_net
      default_router

    In the absence of hiera config, they will be defined
    as their default names, as mentioned above.

WIP: Need to submit custom names for these values once
nailgun supports entering these values.

Change-Id: I900e84627c47054ea24f81e7f61f387048ae1097
Partial-Bug: #1349702

commit_message:
Add astute-version argument to astute-rsync

Astute gem filename needs to match the name on master node in order for
astute container to run updated code.

Change-Id: I2ad3e4c7e879c3228db3e76a54b19996bc821455
Closes-Bug: #1514740

commit_message:
Added upgrade step for extra nova migrations

This adds and documents an upgrade step for additional nova
migrations that need to be done within the kilo cycle time
frame. These migrations will ensure that the cluster is able
to be upgrade to later OpenStack versions.

Change-Id: Iee4cff284355f85b7acb73b753e6448402a344ca
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Backup UUID

added backup_uuid field to backup metadata,

the current behaviour adds a composed backup id which can break the api
by having slashes in it, adding a backup_uuid field prevents that.

Change-Id: Ic4d6f2f1d5f317633c5bf1ca69930881652098fd

commit_message:
Improved horizon dashboard for freezer

action, job, session, backup, clients are now objects in api.py
shield decorator to avoid having boilerplate code in views
move from freezer_ui to disaster_recovery url
improved actions edition in a job
javascript lint
added clients panel
added actions panel
improved restore functionality from the dashboard

Change-Id: I23aed516bcde3a40b24144b05f858d1e3a49a796

Add TripleO stable/liberty to gerritbot channels

We recently started maintaining stable/liberty branches for some
repos, and wish to have IRC notifications of changes to these.

Change-Id: I4e75f766759818652a1c0de8d36f0cb28c6fb8ff

commit_message:
Adding Baseline Capability to the Text Formatter

This commit adds baseline capability to the text formatter.

It will behave as normal with normal results, but if presented
with baseline results it will show candidate issues when
appropriate.

Change-Id: I82e9d6ad830619565c0038a79a7f96ebdfabe51e

commit_message:
Adding baseline capabilities to HTML formatter and update report

This commit adds baseline capabilities to the HTML formatter and
updates the styling of the report.  If baseline results are
provided candidate issues will be shown for any cases where the
matching issue can't be determined.

commit_message:
[Ops Guide] Applying patches: Remove mention of errata

This patch:

- replaces the errata links  with MU links,
- rephrases mentioning of errata with updated info where
  to find the documentation,
- adds an intro sentence to the section,
- corrects small grammar and rst markup mistakes.

Change-Id: I08cb60d534391ff528a4632a44249754b1161d29
Closes-Bug: #1511684

commit_message:
Update Neutron sub-projects using stable branches

Some Neutron sub-projects have been using stable branches for a while
now, and some have recently started. Update projects,yaml to reflect
this by using the correct tags.

Change-Id: Ia36a5054b046e38af1e0d3ae072a6ce0c1fa64eb
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-11 18:23:24.000000000', 'message': 'Shorten the kolla job names

Due to the length of the job name and the tox target we run into an
uncommon limitation; the virtualenv that tox launches is nested in a
path that is too long. This leads to an error on our longest named
job which prevents tox from running properly.

This limitation is the limit for the line length of the first line
in a shell script. In this case <virtualenv>/bin/pip has a path that
exceeds that limit by a few characters. This results in a very
confusing "OSError: [Errno 2] No such file or directory" error.

See `man execve` for more info. A quote from that manpage:
'A maximum line length of 127 characters is allowed for the first line
in a #! executable shell script.'

To reproduce this locally you can just create a very long path and
then run tox in it. Example: http://paste.openstack.org/show/478559/

Change-Id: I51f8f67d9ab139f1d539fce05ce3cc4766aeedff
Depends-On: I43fba2a5ff1890d699045496c9eaee5e849f3e75

commit_message:
Shorten the kolla job names

Due to the length of the job name and the tox target we run into an
uncommon limitation; the virtualenv that tox launches is nested in a
path that is too long. This leads to an error on our longest named
job which prevents tox from running properly.

This limitation is the limit for the line length of the first line
in a shell script. In this case <virtualenv>/bin/pip has a path that
exceeds that limit by a few characters. This results in a very
confusing "OSError: [Errno 2] No such file or directory" error.

See `man execve` for more info. A quote from that manpage:
'A maximum line length of 127 characters is allowed for the first line
in a #! executable shell script.'

To reproduce this locally you can just create a very long path and
then run tox in it. Example: http://paste.openstack.org/show/478559/

Change-Id: I51f8f67d9ab139f1d539fce05ce3cc4766aeedff
Depends-On: I43fba2a5ff1890d699045496c9eaee5e849f3e75

commit_message:
Use assertFalse(observed) instead of assertEqual(False, observed)

The patch also improves the way in which the assertTrue (and
similarly assertFalse) are done,

We should use assertFalse not assertEqual.

Co-Authored-By: Gary Kotton <gkotton@vmware.com>

Closes-Bug: #1503074

commit_message:
Choose virt type automatically

If nova_virt_type variable is not defined in defaults/main.yml,
Using command "egrep -c '(vmx|svm)' /proc/cpuinfo" in
deploy environment, it can easily tell us what the right
virt_type is according to the return value.

If this command returns a value of one or greater, your
compute node supports hardware acceleration and just set
virt_type = kvm.

If this command returns a value of zero, your compute node
does not support hardware acceleration and you must configure
virt_type = qemu instead of kvm.

Change-Id: I6e36ffcb56d50556df0803aea9f4cd7850fada5a

commit_message:
Added logging for haproxy to rsyslog

The change adds logging for haproxy on localhost through the use
of rsyslog which is now a dependency. The logs will be stored in
/var/log/haproxy which will later be indexed and shipped to the
logging server. The change makes it possible to debug issues with
haproxy using specific log files instead of having to go digging
through syslog.

Change-Id: Id942ce159ea45703259f7aff0e5a85780a83370b
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Revert "Revert "Remove TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR in the api tox env""

This reverts commit a3154b03ac60df586bd8fd67f03c20327f2dde41.

The revert was merged too quickly, without waiting for tox project to fix us.
The gate passed for the revert only because infra folks removed images
that had new tox in them. We will be broken by the next images though.

Change-Id: I148c80e5b9512fee280ecbf3ca7498ddf1cfd96d

Fix some nits inside validation/config.py

Inside validation/config there is a few messages that are
wrapped with double quotes as well as one spot where there
is 2 spaces between sentences.

commit_message:
fix heat stable/kilo gate

heat functional jobs were switched to use Aodh which is alarming
functionality split from Ceilometer. this split was only done in
Liberty so Juno and Kilo branches should continue to use Ceilometer
for alarming.

Change-Id: I533fc1cef5c6e619e8ca490cd32eef23aca68ba2

commit_message:
Creation of the tools-contrib repo.

This review creates the tools-contrib directory where it will be a place
to contribute any tool, script, or the like to the OSOps project. The
rename of the tools-generic as a Curated place, is where we plan on
putting coding standards and testing around the tools.

These both were discussed in Tokyo, and decided that we needed a place
for each type.

Change-Id: If8c848fcac4e1a86e0d381883b87cf9dbfdf8b36

searchlight. Requires a new group searchlight-specs-core; initial

commit_message:
Update virtualenv, pip and git existent check in cli-ref tool

In the cli auto generation tool default,
it uses /usr/bin only for virtualenv, pip and git
But ubuntu server installs these two commands to
/usr/local/bin.

This patch searches these commands by the which command.
If it cannot find these commands in the search path,
it reports error.

Closes-Bug: #1515878
Change-Id: I61ed42d27724a5abb72748beb58c1c012c52a3f6

commit_message:
Drop root privileges for rabbitmq

Drop root privileges for rabbitmq.  Only the rabbitmq user
will be able to execute chown of /var/lib/rabbitmq.

Change-Id: I546e6b475a8462bfbc75972854e1fee64f96d9cb
Partially-Implements: blueprint drop-root

commit_message:
Cells: Support external network events

This adds the cells plumbing code necessary for external network events
to be routed to the proper compute host.

Partial-Bug: #1456381
Change-Id: I312fa6e5532a85a2f522827d4e9c3ac919c8eb9e

commit_message:
Update etc/ironic/ironic.conf.sample

This updates etc/ironic/ironic.conf.sample to include the config
'graceful_shutdown_timeout' and to indicate that the port-related
configs expect port values instead of integer values.

The .sample file is updated via running 'tox -egenconfig'.

Change-Id: Id297ee0b095c69491d31fd66261423f0f739fe11

commit_message:
Use assertFalse instead of assertEqual

As the changes have been made for use of assertFalse over assertEqual
for matching false. This patch will do the same change in some
statements which were not covered by previous patches.

Change-Id: I8c9c946067e6814f10f969347fa2c096d24acc48

When security groups were first implemented in this plugin, I had to put
a hack in our custom branch of OVS that made DHCP packets bypass
conntrack.  This issue has now been debugged and fixed.

Part of this patch is switching our default OVS branch to one without
the DHCP hack. We still require a custom branch because we need patches
for the kernel backport of ovs+conntrack integration.  This backport is
up for review so we should be back to OVS master soon.

The first part of the DHCP problem was a bug in ovs conntrack
integration that resulted in the DHCP request not making it to the DHCP
server at all in some cases.  The fix is here:

    https://github.com/openvswitch/ovs/commit/e37b8437e915a02a88116e5ea7af1a7e716bd597

The second part of the DHCP problem is that because of how DHCP works,
it's not a point to point connection that can be tracked and
automatically let responses through.  Instead, we need to explicitly
allow DHCP server responses to reach clients.  The logic here is that if
DHCP is enabled for a subnet, we allow DHCP server responses to reach a
port as long as the source IP adddress is on that subnet.

Change-Id: If14a64af7eba61c8cab752adfbdf8171d0ab2d3a
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Allow DHCP responses to reach clients.

When security groups were first implemented in this plugin, I had to put
a hack in our custom branch of OVS that made DHCP packets bypass
conntrack.  This issue has now been debugged and fixed.

Part of this patch is switching our default OVS branch to one without
the DHCP hack. We still require a custom branch because we need patches
for the kernel backport of ovs+conntrack integration.  This backport is
up for review so we should be back to OVS master soon.

The first part of the DHCP problem was a bug in ovs conntrack
integration that resulted in the DHCP request not making it to the DHCP
server at all in some cases.  The fix is here:

    https://github.com/openvswitch/ovs/commit/e37b8437e915a02a88116e5ea7af1a7e716bd597

The second part of the DHCP problem is that because of how DHCP works,
it's not a point to point connection that can be tracked and
automatically let responses through.  Instead, we need to explicitly
allow DHCP server responses to reach clients.  This is likely temporary
and can be removed once OVN's native DHCP support is merged.

Change-Id: If14a64af7eba61c8cab752adfbdf8171d0ab2d3a
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Remove TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR in the api tox env

Setting TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR in tox.ini is breaking the gate,
probably because of a tox bug [1].
Removing the line to unblock the gate. This implies that
for local execution of the tests TEMPEST_CONFIG_DIR
should be set manually.

[1] https://bitbucket.org/hpk42/tox/issues/285/tox-220-breaks-some-toxini-config-files

Closes-bug: #1515335

Change-Id: I62f7985b034d17626a45ad965265111b671a5974
(cherry picked from commit ad815651de98580afeca6d56319f8c8a50a357e7)

commit_message:
[install] Remove RDO ceilometer swift support

In Kilo, RDO does not package python-ceilometermiddleware
that swift requires for ceilometer integration. For some
reason, the guide suggests using 'pip' to install it which
breaks Python packages managed by the distribution package
management system. Only reasonable solution involves disabling
ceilometer swift support on distributions using RDO packages.

Change-Id: I0364e1a2a1cbf73a9f081b033df61c31de752c61
Closes-Bug: #1514844

commit_message:
Configure horizon with identity v3

Currently horizon configures keystone using v3 only if v2 is not
available. Really we should just always be using v3.

Change-Id: Icac4d90b617209da75abf33f8e25ffc021c45fdb

commit_message:
Set ilo driver to utilize local web server

The ilo driver is inherintly dependent upon swift being available,
so in order to run the server in stand-alone mode with the driver,
we need to set the driver to utilize the local webserver for virtual
media.

Change-Id: I00dd7bcc87a07d0c72d3870461bf8ade9b416a54

commit_message:
Add reno for release-notes

Add reno to automatically generate release notes - the same way other
OpenStack projects do it.
For details see
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-November/078301.html

This adds a version.py file to request the version of the repo.

Change-Id: Ia009f4cf73bd4188af3a126123d688438b97c994

commit_message:
Fix cli-package name check

Replace from -eq to ==,
since this comparison is string (i.e. "gnocchi").

Ref.
https://www.gnu.org/software/bash/manual/bash.html#Bash-Conditional-Expressions

Closes-Bug: #1515842

[{'created': '2015-11-04 21:56:30.000000000', 'message': 'Stop closing part_iter

Doing so apparently causes us to re-enter the current iterator?

This won't regress on the ChunkWriteTimeout error we were seeing in
the unit tests (Clay's test changes are sufficient to address that), but
should fix the func tests previously either:

 * Had several conditional SLO requests 500 instead of 412/304, due to
   "ValueError: generator already executing", or
 * Passed, but still had tracebacks in the proxy log, along the lines of
   "AssertionError: do not call blocking functions from the mainloop"

Change-Id: I075a892f901c18ab5c178c9c4a2f367b76ae78e2
Related-Change: I156d873c72c19623bcfbf39bf120c98800b3cada
'}, {'created': '2015-11-13 02:30:38.000000000', 'message': "Close EC fragment iterators in the GreenThread that's consuming them

Otherwise, we might try to close them while they're already running.
This should prevent conditional SLO requests from returning 500 when
they should have returned 304 or 412.

Change-Id: I075a892f901c18ab5c178c9c4a2f367b76ae78e2
Related-Change: I156d873c72c19623bcfbf39bf120c98800b3cada
"}]
commit_message:
Close EC fragment iterators in the GreenThread that's consuming them

Otherwise, we might try to close them while they're already running.
This should prevent conditional SLO requests from returning 500 when
they should have returned 304 or 412.

Change-Id: I075a892f901c18ab5c178c9c4a2f367b76ae78e2
Related-Change: I156d873c72c19623bcfbf39bf120c98800b3cada

messages:
[{'account_id': 11278, 'date': '2015-10-16 04:30:49.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-16 05:00:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-congress-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/23/235723/1/check/gate-congress-pep8/bca5955/ : SUCCESS in 2m 23s
- gate-congress-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/23/235723/1/check/gate-congress-python27/9c5915c/ : SUCCESS in 3m 25s
- gate-congress-python34 http://logs.openstack.org/23/235723/1/check/gate-congress-python34/ea0ae32/ : FAILURE in 3m 26s (non-voting)
- gate-congress-dsvm-api http://logs.openstack.org/23/235723/1/check/gate-congress-dsvm-api/82532f9/ : SUCCESS in 29m 12s'}, {'account_id': 8878, 'date': '2015-10-16 17:34:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

Please add tests for rows in table with modal.'}, {'account_id': 8878, 'date': '2015-10-16 17:46:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

btw, I don't think Congress needs to return rows for a table with modal now since Congress only allows 'execute' modal in its rule. When the table has rows, Congress executes the action as reactive enforcement then the row would be cleared."}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2015-10-19 04:36:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I don't think we should plan on computing the modal from the service:table string.  Rather, there should be a way of including the modal in that string, e.g. modal[service:table].

Even though that's not necessary today, eventually we want to be able to write both...

insert[p(x)] :- ...

delete[p(x)] :- ...

But if we can compute the modal from the service:tablename, then that would mean we are assuming someone hasn't written both those rules.  

In other words, it's a bug that allows us to compute the modal from just the service:table, so we don't want to build features (especially into the API) that rely on that bug.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2015-10-19 04:36:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 8878, 'date': '2015-10-19 09:36:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Computing rows for 'insert' modal makes sense me when implemented since the modal makes new table. To enable it, I agree Tim's suggestion that requires a user to specify modal name in the string.

On the other hand, rows for 'delete' don't make sense me since the table is already defined as a real rule in a policy."}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-10-30 09:07:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Agree with Tim and Masahito, we shouldn't compute 'execute' table.

I think we can fix this bug 1454844 by the other way.

Now when we create a reactive policy, like: 'execute[nova:servers.pause(x)] :- nova:servers(id=x, status="ACTIVE")
', the tables 'nova:servers.pause' and 'nova:servers' will present in the output of 'congress policy table list', the user might want to list table rows by the table 'nova:servers.pause', that cause this bug, 'nova:servers.pause' is just a service API or user-defined function, not a regular table, so filter this type table out from policy.tablenames(), that should been a quick fix, make sense?

https://github.com/openstack/congress/blob/master/congress/api/row_model.py#L113-L117'}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-10-31 03:21:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Add my patch as an alternative.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/240634/'}, {'account_id': 11278, 'date': '2015-11-03 08:57:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Ruichen, Thanks for the patch. But with this patch, it doesn't compute rows for any table with modal right? As Masahito mentioned in the comment, do we need to allow to compute rows with insert modal or likewise?"}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2015-11-03 12:47:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Yeah, if we decide to support insert/delete modal in Congress, I can do some minor adjustments on my patch to filter out insert modal, insert/delete modal don't present in current Congress, so my patch don't handle these."}, {'account_id': 8878, 'date': '2015-11-05 14:30:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Anusha and Rui, I agree both. This is my idea to resolve the bug and to enable Congress to compute table with modal. To achive the goal, there are 2 steps.

1st step: To stop error Janet reported in bug 1454844, we'll fix the bug with a way Rui mentioned. It means a patch for this bug stops Congress to return tables with modal when users call table list API.

2nd step: We implements a new BP which enables Congress to retrieve table with modal. We could disscuss which modal Congress support in table list API and row list API. It doesn't barrier to fix the bug.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:07:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Anusha: You +1ed @Rui's alternative patch.  Does that mean we're abandoning this one?  If so, could you use the Abandon button to do that?"}, {'account_id': 11278, 'date': '2015-11-13 04:51:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Tim, Yes, Rui's alternative patch looks good to me to address this problem. I'll abandon mine. Thanks."}, {'account_id': 11278, 'date': '2015-11-13 04:53:13.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abandoning, as https://review.openstack.org/#/c/240634/ addresses the issue.'}]

commit_message:
pass modal argument when querying for arity

Currently, modal argument is ignored always when getting arity.
This causes error and unable to get the arity for the table with
modal. This commit addresses the issue.

Closes-Bug:#1454844
Change-Id: I40218c4e81b912eb3925259612bccc2db36675d4

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-23 03:41:11.000000000', 'message': 'Add OpenID Connect RP Apache Module[WIP]

This patch set adds bits to configure the OpenID Connect
relying party apache module.
This is so any OpenID Connect provider may be used as an
identity provider with federated keystone.

There were a few changes in the logic to make this work.

* keystone_federated_auth_methods variable was added so the
  user can specify supported federated auth modules. The code
  also uses this variable to determine if the oidc apache
  module directives will be applied (it looks for oidc).

* keystone_federated_saml_implementations variable was added
  to help with applying the right apache module configs. This
  is a list of saml implementations that is used to apply the
  corresponding apache configs. Currently only Shibboleth is
  supported.

* Before, the code would check if keystone_sp object is defined
  then apply the Shibboleth apache configs. Now, the variables
  mentioned above will help with deciding which apache configs to
  apply.

Other changes:

* Added example trusted_idp_list entry for the google OIDC server.
  (Still need to test if the cliams match up)

* Moved the keystone_sp docs to user_variables.yml

* Loading keystone_sp facts earlier in the playbooks.
  That way we can take advantage of those facts in the subsequent
  plays.

All feedback welcome!

Change-Id: I18ed0b76d0066ea52a0bd677ee01ffde45fa9de9

commit_message:
Add OpenID Connect RP Apache Module

This patch set adds bits to configure the OpenID Connect
relying party apache module.
This is so any OpenID Connect provider may be used as an
identity provider with federated keystone.

There were a few changes in the logic to make this work.

* keystone_federated_auth_methods variable was added so the
  user can specify supported federated auth modules. The code
  also uses this variable to determine if the oidc apache
  module directives will be applied (it looks for oidc).

* keystone_federated_saml_implementations variable was added
  to help with applying the right apache module configs. This
  is a list of saml implementations that is used to apply the
  corresponding apache configs. Currently only Shibboleth is
  supported.

* Before, the code would check if keystone_sp object is defined
  then apply the Shibboleth apache configs. Now, the variables
  mentioned above will help with deciding which apache configs to
  apply.

* The mod_auth_openidc module uses the memcached servers to for
  caching data to use across multiple keystone nodes.

Other changes:

* Added example trusted_idp_list entry for the google OIDC server.

* Moved the keystone_sp docs to user_variables.yml

* Loading keystone_sp facts earlier in the playbooks.
  That way we can take advantage of those facts in the subsequent
  plays.

All feedback welcome!

Change-Id: I18ed0b76d0066ea52a0bd677ee01ffde45fa9de9

commit_message:
Use oslo_config new type PortOpt for port options

The oslo_config library provides new type PortOpt to validate the
range of port now.

Change-Id: I8d1746c399268d7b3388db82de77c5e6c06844a3
ref: https://github.com/openstack/oslo.config/blob/2.6.0/oslo_config/cfg.py#L1114

I think the code is fine, and is a useful utility. To me, I think all these default values should be specified in a configuration file. I would want them all out of the code, and referenced from this singular file.

There is a timeout that is retrieved from configuration, and for consistency, all these defaults should be specified there as well.

I'm not sure if this is possible, but if it isn't, maybe at a minimum these are constant values. I am just thinking in terms of long term maintenance of the code."}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2015-11-13 02:04:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I think it's not the point of this bug.
The problem is 'min_size' and 'max_size' can be assigned to None in the database, so if pass 'null' or 'None' to cluster API, API should convert them to the default value.( min_size -> 0, max_size -> -1).

So you just need to make this conversion in the entrance of cluster API.

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/senlin/tree/senlin/api/openstack/v1/clusters.py#n44"}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2015-11-13 02:06:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Made a mistake in the comment above:

The problem is 'min_size' and 'max_size' can be assigned to None in the database

->

The problem is 'min_size' and 'max_size' can't be assigned to None in the database"}, {'account_id': 7404, 'date': '2015-11-13 02:37:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi xu-haiwei, actually this patch fixes this bug by correctly setup default value during cluster creation. Because we can accept None for min_size/max_size for cluster update, so it's not ok to set a default in ClusterData, since it's used for cluster update. See https://github.com/openstack/senlin/blob/master/senlin/api/openstack/v1/clusters.py#L212-L213

Setting this min_size/max_size default value is at https://github.com/openstack/senlin/blob/master/senlin/engine/cluster.py#L70-L72 , but it's not correctly handle it, that's why I add this function."}, {'account_id': 7404, 'date': '2015-11-13 02:40:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Junio, thanks for the suggestions, how about add some default value at https://github.com/openstack/senlin/blob/master/senlin/common/consts.py ?'}, {'account_id': 15642, 'date': '2015-11-13 02:51:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

I think that would be perfect Ethan.'}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2015-11-13 02:55:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

https://github.com/openstack/senlin/blob/master/senlin/engine/cluster.py#L70-L72

This is the bug.

You should change it like this:

self.min_size = kwargs.get('min_size') or 0
self.max_size = kwargs.get('max_size') or -1

This change can solve all the problems I think."}, {'account_id': 11034, 'date': '2015-11-13 03:01:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi, Ethan, I think I agree with Haiwei that maybe we don't need to handle all kwargs value getting cases using extract_kwargs function. We just need to apply it on cases where 'None' is illegal value of keyword argument, e.g. min_size, max_size of cluster."}, {'account_id': 11034, 'date': '2015-11-13 03:05:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Sorry, just posted part of the comment...

Since for an attribute which is allowed to set to None, {'ATTR_NAME': None} should be treated as an legal input and kwargs.get('ATTR_NAME', None) is actually a correct logic to handle it."}, {'account_id': 7404, 'date': '2015-11-13 03:47:59.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Will follow xuhaiwei's suggestion to fix this bug."}]

commit_message:
Add extract_kwargs functions to utils.py

Add extract_kwargs functiosn to utils.py, and use it for cluster.
For following kwargs:
{
  'foo': None
}

kwargs.get('foo', 'bar') will return None

New added function will return 'bar'.
extract_kwargs({'foo': None}, key='foo', default='bar')

Change-Id: Ic822618f47d66e81a35c21e320cdd463bfcc4bd0
Closes-Bug: #1515134

commit_message:
Clarify the behaviour for the "require" thread policy

This removes any ambiguity around the behaviour when the "require"
thread policy is specified.

The previous wording would have opened up the possibility of scheduling
on a host without hyperthreads enabled.

Change-Id: I5d624c37f882df897391531e5639d731fd4744d9

commit_message:
Improve parameters obtaining logic from adopt stack data

Use empty dict as default parameters value, if environment section
or parameters section within environment doesn't be set in the
adopt stack data file.

Change-Id: I7ef9dbf41fb0bcff2ca3b7bc80af00bb737d4807
Closes-Bug: #1510832

commit_message:
Add a disabled by ports -> files healthcheck plugin

Since most openstack applications do not run on a single
port it is useful to be able to have a single healthcheck
plugin that can respond to requests for different ports with
different files; this way for example keystone admin port can
be disabled while its public port can be kept active (without
having to run two different applications, one for the admin
endpoint and one for the public endpoint).

Change-Id: I0bafb5a2091e54c9f01f24812438296b75afaf63

commit_message:
Selectively prune /root for ironic-agent ramdisk

Previously all files in /root were ignored when building the
ironic-agent ramdisk. This prevented for example to use the
local-config element to connect to the ramdisk via ssh as root user.

This commit change the exclude rule on /root to only ignore the
/root/.cache directory.

Change-Id: I18d839e8d97636f5f2164ba407f252407d9bc956
Closes-Bug: #1451668

commit_message:
Decouple transport for RPC and Notification

Add a new configuration option for setting up
an alternate notification_transport_url that
can be used for notifications. This allows
operators to separate the transport mechanisms
used for RPC and Notifications.

DocImpact

Closes-Bug: #1504622
Change-Id: Ief6f95ea906bfd95b3218a930c9db5d8a764beb9

commit_message:
Move AuthContext middleware into its own file

AuthContext middleware is quite a lot more complex than most of the
other things in the middleware.core directory. Move it out to its own
file before starting to refactor.

Change-Id: Ia9da577495b8ebc2a6ddeffc02e07b458c8f3a97

commit_message:
Deprecate Extensible Resource Tracker

We agreed at the Summit to remove the ERT. Before doing that, we need to
advertise the entrypoint consumers that they need to consider an alternative.

Release Notes should announce that too.

Co-Authored-By: Paul Murray <pmurray@hpe.com>

UpgradeImpact

Change-Id: Ie4b6670a828d99aebfd348bd700f9f58b3e39fdb

commit_message:
Set ZUUL_BRANCH using BRANCH if not available

In most cases, ZUUL_BRANCH is set in gate, but not all the time. One
exception is e.g. periodic stable jobs, where there is no actual patch
to validate, hence no ZUUL_REF or ZUUL_BRANCH is set. In that case, we
need to help zuul-cloner to determine the proper branch to fetch
neutron.

It could be achieved by e.g. hardcoding the branch using --zuul_branch
CLI argument passed into zuul-cloner. In this patch, I instead set
ZUUL_BRANCH to BRANCH that seems to be always present in all kinds of
jobs. It is then used by zuul-cloner to choose the correct branch.

This will be needed in the future when we spin out stable/mitaka and run
stable periodic jobs for neutron-fwaas.

Change-Id: I360239a1443f8d4e16210a1ef743912e1bf85f41

commit_message:
Copy the env to the backup stack in failed update

When an update fails, we currently update the environment of the stack
to contain both the new and old parameters and types. Unfortunately we
don't do that for the backup stack which is reused. This patch adds the
environment change.

Change-Id: I4dc5dd35e4aeee498dd8960a1000913e97b924d5
Closes-Bug: 1508096

commit_message:
Revert "Add Pillow to docs-requirements.txt"

This reverts commit d41599e5a500163c1010bf02f5cb07bfff14f25c.

Adding Pillow to *requirements.txt was a temporary way to set the
upper bound to < 3.0.0

nodepool thick slaves and requirements have been fixed and devstack is
fixed in the patch that this depends on.

Change-Id: I05bed9356b9840df620c0808a7d0c5c8e3a318c0
Depends-On: I2bec8cf1bfeaaa6ae329704229fdeb86d26e55c7

Added the configuration options to allow the administrator to configure
the collector to only record samples or events selectively. If
record_samples or record_events is configured false, the collector won't
consume the notifications respectively.

the certain record_metering_data or record_events capabilities won't be
loaded.

commit_message:
Configure collector to only record meter or event

Added the configuration options to allow the administrator to configure
the collector to only record meter or event by setting the
meter_dispatchers and event_dispatchers configuration.

Separated dispatcher managers load the dispatchers from different
namespaces for meter/event respectively.

Doc-Impact: separated meter/event dispatchers

Change-Id: I161318f4503ce79205b54a93f2ae9b4e052f7971
Closes-Bug: #1480333

other *NotFounds and remove old *NotFound exception
classes definition.

Closes-Bug: #1461343

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-02 19:16:03.000000000', 'message': 'Add a tool that can extract author information for oslo projects

This script will download the oslo repositories and then create
a per project html report with authorship information about each
project (which can then be viewed in your favorite web browser).

This will be used to see who could be a new oslo core recruit(s)
as core reviewers, or just as general useful things to know...

Change-Id: I780e39e353b06cadc1023bafe165b398e3f5a5d4

commit_message:
Add a tool that can extract author information for oslo projects

This script will download the oslo repositories and then create
a per project html report with authorship information about each
project (which can then be viewed in your favorite web browser).

This will be used to see who could be a new oslo core recruit(s)
as core reviewers, or just as general useful things to know...

Change-Id: I780e39e353b06cadc1023bafe165b398e3f5a5d4

commit_message:
Fix grub-efi-amd64-signed install failure

When build ubuntu iso image, it will install grub-efi-amd64-signed
and grub-efi-amd64 packages. Both of the postinst script will try
to find root device and install grub which will definitely fail in
such a chroot environment.
So the workaround is to skip error and remove postinst script.

Fixed bug #1491280

Change-Id: I2b2d0686e2f8ab8c88222f3dc777c607be4d84a4

commit_message:
py3: Replace unicode with six.text_type

* Replace unicode with six.text_type
* Replace (str, unicode) with six.string_types

This change makes modified code compatible with Python 3.

Move also imports in cue/api/controllers/v1/cluster.py to respect the
OpenStack coding style on imports.

The initial patch was generated by the unicode operation of the sixer
tool.

Change-Id: Ib53087f74d52fe60381e8cca2f0209d39f09e24d

commit_message:
Add gnocchi to common and CLI reference

Add gnocchi to Chapter 1
   (for CLI Ref)
Add gnocchi to Appendix
   (common part includes CLI Ref/Config Ref)
Add gnocchi CLI Ref XML 2.0.0 (autogenerated)

Ref
Gnocchi  Ceilometer API v3
https://specs.openstack.org/openstack/ceilometer-specs/specs/juno/gnocchi.html

P.S.
some comments are missing periods in autogenerated file.
I post it to gnocchiclient separately.

Change-Id: I548bbadee2c42b3d23d1a5be6403cba6f2a88079

commit_message:
[Verify] Don't mask original exc if failure happens

We shouldn't mask the original exception and traceback
if any failure happens when we create a Tempest resource.
So this patch is intended to fix the issue. Also exception
"TempestResourceCreationFailure" was removed from exceptions.py
because this one is not used anywhere now.

Change-Id: I3edbefb11430f4bf5279efbd89ccc297f2fb84db

commit_message:
Implementing ONOS ML2 plugin support

This Open Network Operating System (ONOS) using neutron ML2 Plugin,
Implementation and Neutron integration.

Change-Id: I3089f61f1893d3d75274f244aadcefff48c096b1

commit_message:
Revert "Add Pillow to test-requirements.txt"

This reverts commit 29478cbd7a8f3c848cd0c6f858798b18f7ec2ac4.

29478cbd7a8f3c848cd0c6f858798b18f7ec2ac4 was a quick fix to work around
missing libraries needed by Pillow 3.0.0.

This librarries have been added to devstack and thick slaves so this
hack is no longer needed in ironic.

There are out-standing reviews sitting in the queue that need to be reviewed prior to this one.'}, {'account_id': 16168, 'date': '2015-10-20 05:38:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Just out of curiosity. Why making all fields required for the PUT while in the same time not every field is required for POST (according to AlarmDefinitionResource, not PUTvsPOST eternal battle). 

I mean, while you are using POST you clearly state "create a new resource, new entity" for me whereas for PUT it looks like "please update the resource, but hey, if you cannot find it, just create it". So having all fields as required seems reasonable for me if I think about it as idempotent endpoint that either creates or updates and will never return error code saying that you are trying to overwrite something that does actually exist (i.e HTTP Conflict). 

What comes to down to conclusion
> CreateAlarmDefinitionCommand lacks certain @NotNull values
> PUT,POST should share definition command

What do you think ?'}, {'account_id': 14517, 'date': '2015-11-09 20:54:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Apologies for the (very) late response.

For the API, at the moment, PUT is only used for updates. On POST requests, there are fields which can be frequently left empty (ex. an empty list for undetermined actions) so it makes sense to allow the user to omit the field and automatically fill it with a default. In contrast it is more unexpected to receive a default value in a PUT request if a field is omitted, so it is better to require the exact input and notify the user if they didn't specify a value. Incidentally, we have a field in the PUT request ("actions_enabled") that is not allowed in the POST request which I will fix.

Also, could you remove the -2 Roland? This change shouldn't be in front of anything older now.'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-11-10 04:57:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 14517, 'date': '2015-11-10 18:00:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-10 18:16:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Enhance test_metric_names and test_alarms_state_history

Send a metric, wait for it to be stored, then query the names
resource to check if it is valid.

Fix some issues with the limit/offset tests for tests_alarm_state_history.

Fix an issue with test_list_measurements_with_offset_limit where the
iteration was just one too many.

Change-Id: Iaad8ae1ee43525ad4fa83bf77fcfe3914cfdf314
